{"title_page": "Julian Casablancas", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Julian Casablancas\n| image              = [[File:Julian Casablancas @ Lollapalooza 2014 (13657827913).jpg|center|250px]]\n| caption            = Casablancas performing at Lollapalooza 2014\n| birth_name         = Julian Fernando Casablancas\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1978|8|23}}\n| birth_place        = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Singer|musician|songwriter|record producer}}\n| years_active       = 1998\u2013present\n| relatives          = [[John Casablancas]] (father)\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Juliet Joslin|2005|2019|end=div}}\n| children           = 2\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background = solo_singer\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Indie rock]]|[[alternative rock]]|[[garage rock revival]]|[[New wave music|new wave]]|[[experimental rock]]}}\n| instrument = {{hlist|Vocals|guitar|keyboards|drums|bass guitar}}\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Cult Records|Cult]]|[[Rough Trade Records|Rough Trade]]|[[RCA Records|RCA]]}}\n| associated_acts = {{hlist|[[The Strokes]]|[[Julian Casablancas+The Voidz|The Voidz]]|[[Albert Hammond Jr.]]|[[The Growlers]]|[[Daft Punk]]|[[Queens of the Stone Age]]}}\n| website    = {{URL|juliancasablancas.com}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Julian Fernando Casablancas''' (born August 23, 1978) is an American singer, musician, songwriter, and record producer. He is best known as the lead singer and primary songwriter of American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[The Strokes]].\n\nIn 2009, Casablancas released a solo album, ''[[Phrazes for the Young]]'', and in 2013 he formed [[experimental rock]] outfit Julian Casablancas + The Voidz, now known simply as [[The Voidz]], with whom he has released two albums: ''[[Tyranny (The Voidz album)|Tyranny]]'' (2014) and ''[[Virtue (The Voidz album)|Virtue]]'' (2018).\n\nAlso in 2009, Casablancas founded [[independent record label]] [[Cult Records]],<ref>Blistein, Jon.[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/julian-casablancas-previews-new-album-with-rioters-and-video-games-20140306 Julian Casablancas Previews New Album With Rioters and Video Games\"] ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' March 6, 2014.</ref> which currently represents artists such as [[The Growlers]], [[Rey Pila]], and [[Karen O]].<ref>[http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/kobalt-label-services-partners-with-cult-records/058825 Kobalt Label Services partners with Cult Records]. June 25, 2014</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nJulian Fernando Casablancas was born in [[New York City]] on August 23, 1978,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themodernage.co.uk/julianx.html|title=Julian Casablancas profile|publisher=themodernage.co.uk|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071122004758/http://www.themodernage.co.uk/julianx.html|archivedate=November 22, 2007|url-status=dead|accessdate=August 9, 2011}}</ref> the son of American business mogul [[John Casablancas]], best known as the founder of [[Elite Model Management]], and Danish former model Jeanette Christiansen, who was crowned the 1965 [[Miss Universe Denmark|Miss Denmark]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VeUCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA38|title=Girl Crazy|last=Prince|first=Dinah|date=January 25, 1988|work=New York Magazine|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=38|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2013/jul/24/john-casablancas|title=John Casablancas obituary|last=Horwell|first=Veronica|date=July 24, 2013|work=The Guardian|access-date=October 25, 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> He has [[Catalans|Catalan]] ancestry on his father's side. When Casablancas was eight, his parents divorced. He once stated that he wanted to be closer to his father, and this \"translated into teenage rebelliousness\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/julian-casablancas-radical-reinvention-20141015|title=Julian Casablancas' Radical Reinvention|last=Doyle|first=Patrick|date=October 15, 2014|work=Rolling Stone}}</ref> His mother subsequently married painter Sam Adoquei.<ref name=\"save you\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.gq.com/story/julian-casablancas |title=Julian Casablancas Is Done Trying to Save You |last=Davidson |first=Zach Baron, Eric Ray |date=September 18, 2014 |work=GQ |access-date=October 25, 2017 |language=en}}</ref> Adoquei helped shape Casablancas' early musical taste by exposing him to music such as [[The Doors]], which was markedly different from the mostly [[Phil Collins]]-influenced music he listened to as a child.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/oct/04/julian-casablancas-strokes-interview |title=Julian Casablancas: 'Does my mind just go blank? Yeah, all the time' |last=Wood |first=Gaby |date=October 3, 2009 |work=The Guardian |access-date=October 25, 2017 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nCasablancas has known the bassist of The Strokes, [[Nikolai Fraiture]], since they were six,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/the-making-of-the-strokes-20020411|title=The Making of the Strokes|last=Eliscu|first=Jenny|date=April 11, 2002|work=Rolling Stone}}</ref> while both were attending [[Lyc\u00e9e Fran\u00e7ais de New York]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lfnyalumni.org/en/classmate/classmateresults/classmateresults.php?criteria=1997 |title=AALFNY: Find a Classmate |publisher=Lfnyalumni.org |date= |accessdate=March 20, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lfnyalumni.org/en/classmate/classmateresults/classmateresults.php?criteria=1996 |title=AALFNY: Find a Classmate |publisher=Lfnyalumni.org |date=January 26, 2009 |accessdate=March 20, 2011}}</ref> When he was 13, Casablancas' father sent him to [[Institut Le Rosey]], a boarding school in [[Switzerland]], where he met future Strokes member [[Albert Hammond, Jr.|Albert Hammond Jr.]]<ref name=\"jimdero1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.jimdero.com/OtherWritings/OtherStrokes.htm|title=The Strokes|last=DeRogatis|first=Jim|date=November 2001|website=Jimdero.com|publisher=Penthouse|access-date=March 20, 2011}}</ref> Casablancas later returned to New York and attended [[Dwight School]] with two other future Strokes, [[Nick Valensi]] and [[Fabrizio Moretti]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://issuu.com/thedwightschool/docs/dwight_1995_reduced/105|title=Dwight 1995|work=Issuu|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"jimdero1\" /> Casablancas never finished high school, but took a [[General Educational Development|GED]] and continued to take music classes at [[Five Towns College]], where he says he first enjoyed himself in class.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NG1PsNK2_Bw |title=Road Tripping with Julian Casablancas |website=YouTube |publisher=BBC Radio |access-date=July 5, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2003/oct/31/2?INTCMP=SRCH | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Neil | last=Strauss | title=Neil Strauss spends seven days with the Strokes | date=October 31, 2003}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=deD1CQAAQBAJ|title=Meet Me in the Bathroom: Rebirth and Rock and Roll in New York City 2001-2011|last=Goodman|first=Lizzy|date=May 23, 2017|publisher=HarperCollins|year=|isbn=9780062233127|location=|pages=|language=en|quote=I left and got a GED and went to Five Towns, which is a vocational music school that anyone can go to.}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== The Strokes (1998\u2013present) ===\n{{Main|The Strokes}}\n[[File:The Strokes by Roger Woolman.jpg|thumb|left|Casablancas with the Strokes in 2002]]\nUpon meeting future guitarist [[Nick Valensi]] and drummer [[Fabrizio Moretti|Fab Moretti]] at Dwight School in Manhattan, the three began to play music together. He reconnected with guitarist [[Albert Hammond Jr.|Albert Hammond Jr]]. when the latter moved to New York. The band was formed in 1998 when Hammond was accepted into the band,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/feb/27/the-strokes-angles-casablancas-interview|title=The Strokes: 'All that Spinal Tap bullshit has gone out the window'|last=Hoby|first=Hermione|date=February 27, 2011|work=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref> with Casablancas as the lead vocalist and main songwriter and Nikolai Fraiture on bass.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=crQoYila-dAC&pg=PA74&lpg=PA74|title=Gang of Five|last=Klosterman|first=Chuck|date=December 2003|publisher=Spin|isbn=|location=|pages=74|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe band began rehearsing a fourteen-song set which included \"Alone, Together\", \"Barely Legal\", \"[[Last Nite]]\", \"[[The Modern Age]]\", \"New York City Cops\", \"Soma\", \"Someday\", \"Take It or Leave It\" and \"This Life\" (an early version of \"Trying Your Luck\"). Most of these songs now feature different lyrics. A demo sent to the newly reformed [[Rough Trade Records]] in the UK sparked interest there, leading to their first release via the website of the UK magazine, ''[[NME]],'' who gave away a free mp3 download of \"[[Last Nite]]\" a week prior to the physical release as part of ''[[The Modern Age]] EP'' in 2001. The EP sparked a bidding war among record labels, the largest for a rock and roll band in years. Shortly after, The Strokes' critically acclaimed debut album ''[[Is This It]]'' was released.\n\nThe band has received the highest of praise for ''Is This It,'' and it set the stage for what people expected to \u201csave rock\u201d in the new millennium.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gq.com/story/the-strokes-retrospective|title=The Fifteen-Year Decline of the Strokes|last=Nguyen|first=Kevin|date=2016-08-12|work=GQ|access-date=2018-11-30|language=en}}</ref> Though some would argue that such statements left unreasonably sized shoes to fill, The Strokes are still highly recognized as one of the most influential garage rock bands of the early 2000s, paving the way for many new alternative bands to come.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2017/05/26/how-the-strokes-helped-make-nyc-the-worlds-sexy-rock-capital/|title=The inside story of the band that defined the 2000s|date=2017-05-26|work=New York Post|access-date=2018-11-30|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nStatistically, all albums released following their debut were not nearly as successful or well-received by fans and critics.<ref>{{Citation|title=The Strokes|date=2018-11-15|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=The_Strokes&oldid=868990975|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2018-11-30}}</ref> In an excerpt from Lizzie Goodman's ''Meet Me in the Bathroom: Rebirth and Rock and Roll in New York City, 2001-2011-'' named after The Strokes' track- Strokes guitarist, Nick Valensi, comments, ''\"''With ''[[Room on Fire]]'' [2003], people were giving us shit because they said we were sounding too much the same. With the third album [''[[First Impressions of Earth]]''], we were getting shit that we don\u2019t sound like ''Room on Fire''. We got fucked by the same thing twice!\"<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.vulture.com/2017/05/the-strokes-an-oral-history.html|title=How the Strokes \u2014 and the Early-Aughts New York Rock Boom \u2014 Went Bust|last=Goodman|first=Lizzy|work=Vulture|access-date=2018-11-30|language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[File:StrokesBrooklyn311219-237.jpg|thumb|right|Casablancas performing with the Strokes on New Year's Eve 2019]]\n\nAfter the release of the two other albums and several major tours, the band took a 5-year break before returning with their fourth album [[Angles (The Strokes album)|''Angles'']] in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/article/7925-this-is-it-ten-years-of-the-strokes/|title=This Is It: Ten Years of the Strokes|last=Garrett|first=Jonathan|date=March 7, 2011|website=Pitchfork|language=en}}</ref> The five-year hiatus was said to be the result of conflicting solo projects, sobriety issues, and unspoken emotions.The Strokes' drummer Fab Moretti claimed the band struggled to process such \"subconscious volcanic emotions\", partly because they were still \"children\" at the time.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nThough their creative processes has been critiqued by outside observers as \u201ca democracy under a dictator\u201d,<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/nymetro/news/culture/features/15495/index6.html|title=Group Therapy|website=NYMag.com|access-date=2018-11-26}}</ref> Casablancas has encouraged each band member to contribute their own ideas and collectively sort through which ones will potentially turn into something more.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.clashmusic.com/features/julian-casablancas-interview|title=Julian Casablancas Interview|work=Clash Magazine|access-date=2018-11-30|language=en}}</ref> Commenting on the meticulous nature of Julian's creative process, guitarist, Nick Valensi, has said, \u201chis ear is so sharp. He\u2019s the one with the ear for detail in this band. Creatively, he is a force to be reckoned with.\u201d<ref name=\":6\" /> The 2011 release, ''Angles,'' is said to reflect the beginning of the more collaborative nature of the band's creative process.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/13/arts/music/the-strokes-embrace-group-dynamics-in-a-new-album.html|title=The Strokes Embrace Group Dynamics in a New Album|last=Ryzik|first=Melena|access-date=2018-11-30|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe album release was followed by several headlining appearances at musical festivals, including Reading, Coachella, Lollapalooza and Austin City Limits.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/q-a-julian-casablancas-on-his-solo-album-and-the-strokes-return-20100819 |title=Q&A: Julian Casablancas on His Solo Album and the Strokes' Return |last=Hiatt |first=Brian |date= August 19, 2010 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=October 25, 2017}}</ref> The band released ''[[Comedown Machine]]'' in 2013, as their last album under the contract with long-time label [[RCA Records|RCA]], for which they did no promotion.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://entertainment.time.com/2013/03/26/the-strokes-wipe-the-slate-clean-on-comedown-machine/|title=The Strokes Wipe the Slate Clean on Comedown Machine|last=Roffman|first=Michael|work=Time|access-date=October 25, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0040-781X}}</ref> The band released an EP, ''[[Future Present Past]]'', on Casablancas' own label Cult Records in 2016.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/the-strokes-preview-future-present-past-ep-with-new-song-oblivius-20160526 |title=Strokes Preview New EP With Blistering New Songs |last=Blistein |first=Jon |date=May 26, 2016 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=October 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, it was announced that the band would headline at [[Bilbao BBK Live]] in 2019, kicking off their global comeback.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2018/12/the-strokes-global-comeback-2019/|title=The Strokes plotting \"global comeback\" for 2019|date=2018-12-17|website=Consequence of Sound|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> Numerous dates for festivals and shows have been announced afterwards, including a show at the [[Governors Ball Music Festival]], marking the band's return to New York City.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/governors-ball-2019-lineup-announced-the-strokes-tyler-lil-wayne-sza-more/|title=Governors Ball 2019 Lineup Announced: The Strokes, Tyler, Lil Wayne, SZA, More|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref>\n\nStarting May 14, 2019, The Strokes teased some of new songs, starting with \"The Adults are Talking\", live at [[Pellissier Building and Wiltern Theatre|The Wiltern]] in Los Angeles, giving remarks that there is possibilities for the Strokes to release a new album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-strokes-the-adults-are-talking-live-835099/|title=Watch The Strokes Debut New Song 'The Adults Are Talking'|last=Zemler|first=Emily|last2=Zemler|first2=Emily|date=2019-05-14|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> In December 31, 2019 at Brooklyn NYE, they performed \"Ode to the Mets\", as an offer from Casablancas to sing live instead of singing songs from ''Angles'' as requested by fans. \u201cI don\u2019t remember ''Angles''. What\u2019s ''Angles''?\u201d Casablancas responded before suggesting that the band play the new song and later confirming the release of a new project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2020/1/the-strokes-new-album-announcement-ode-to-the-mets-single|title=The Strokes Announce New Album, Debut New Single \"Ode to the Mets\"|website=HYPEBEAST|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, The Strokes released their newest album, ''[[The New Abnormal]]'', which has been receiving positive reviews among critics, where suggesting the band came back with a better maturity and cohesion among bandmates. The album project was started far back to 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://diymag.com/2016/10/11/the-strokes-new-album-2017-nick-valensi-interview|title=The Strokes are \u201cslowly but surely working on an album\u201d|last=Subscribe|website=diymag.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\n=== Solo projects (2009\u2013present) ===\n[[File:Flickr - moses namkung - Julian Casablancas-2.jpg|thumb|200px|left|Casablancas performing as a solo artist in 2009]]\nAs a solo artist, Casablancas set out with an intention to say what was on his mind, both musically and lyrically.<ref name=\":1\" /> Speaking on his experience as a solo artist versus releasing music with The Strokes, the singer has put it simply, \u201cit\u2019s like touring with me or with five of me,\u201d meaning that each member has their own opinionated state of mind. While such statements raised much concern for the relations between the band members, Casablancas claims that in pursuit of a solo career, he is protecting the integrity of the [Strokes] vibe.<ref>{{Citation|last=Beat Magazine|title=Julian Casablancas Interview|date=2010-05-22|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TRtj6wQngg4&t=400s|access-date=2018-11-09}}</ref> In having a musical project separate from The Strokes, he is able to \u201cchase down any idea [he] wants\u201d, which he would refrain from doing with the band.<ref>{{Citation|last=PerryPoucheen|title=Julian Casablancas - Interview.|date=2011-05-28|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d2ryXJJKXP4&list=PLLZeeZuy6roL7ocqOmOliMSrTX-r3XZCz|access-date=2018-11-09}}</ref>\n\nHis first solo album, ''[[Phrazes for the Young]]'' (inspired by the [[Oscar Wilde]] book \"Phrases and Philosophies for the Use of the Young\"), was released on November 2 in the UK and November 3, 2009, in the United States.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/01/arts/music/01ryzi.html|title=Julian Casablancas, Thriving on Sunshine With a Solo CD|last=Ryzik|first=Melena|date=October 28, 2009|work=The New York Times|access-date=October 25, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Recorded in Omaha, Nebraska, and Casablancas' home city New York, the album was produced by Jason Lader, with additional production from [[Bright Eyes (band)|Bright Eyes]]' [[Mike Mogis]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/the-strokes/46099|title=The Strokes\u2019 Julian Casablancas to release solo album|last=Stokes|first=Paul Stokes|date=July 14, 2009|publisher=NME|access-date=March 20, 2011}}</ref> The album was strongly influenced by [[New wave music|new wave]] and [[electronica]], with Casablancas utilizing [[synthesizer]]s for many songs. He discussed his new influences by saying \"I would've gone weirder with the music, but I wanted to be smart. I didn't want people to say, 'Okay, this is his weird abstract thing,' and dismiss the album. I worked too hard on it for that to happen...I wanted to be crazy original and bridge the gap between traditional music and modern music.\"<ref name=\"SPINterview\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2009/11/spin-interview-julian-casablancas/|title=The SPIN Interview: Julian Casablancas|last=Marchese|first=David|date=October 28, 2009|website=Spin|publisher=Spin Media LLC|access-date=April 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\nJulian Casablancas made his live solo debut for a private party for fashion brand Opening Ceremony in Tokyo, Japan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2009/09/strokes-julian-casablancas-debuts-solo-tunes/|title=Strokes' Julian Casablancas Debuts Solo Tunes|date=September 1, 2009|publisher=Spin.com|access-date=September 18, 2011}}</ref> To celebrate the release of the EP, Casablancas performed a series of shows in October 2009 at The Downtown Palace Theatre in Los Angeles with his live show band, The Sick Six. Members of The Sick Six include [[Jeffrey Kite|Jeff Kite]] (keyboard), Nelson London (synthesizer), JP Bowersock (guitar), [[Danielle Haim]] (percussion) and [[Alex Carapetis]] (drums).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.juliancasablancas.com/news/2010/03/26/id-now-like-to-introduce-the-band|title=I\u2019d Now Like to Introduce the Band|publisher=JulianCasablancas.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402214143/http://www.juliancasablancas.com/news/2010/03/26/id-now-like-to-introduce-the-band|archivedate=April 2, 2012|url-status=dead|accessdate=September 18, 2011}}</ref> Casablancas then toured with The Sick Six in Europe, United States, Australia and Japan from November 2009 until July 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/entertainment/music/frontmans-stroke-of-genius/2010/03/11/1268203345769.html?page=2|title=Frontman's stroke of genius - Music - Entertainment - theage.com.au|date=March 12, 2010|website=The Age|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2010/05/07/music/julians-stroke-of-genius/|title=Julian's stroke of genius|last=Curran|first=Shaun|date=May 7, 2010|work=The Japan Times|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.purepeople.com/article/jamiroquai-phoenix-et-julian-casablancas-la-bretagne-leur-dit-merci_a60183/1|title=Jamiroquai, Phoenix et Julian Casablancas... La Bretagne leur dit merci !|date=July 19, 2010|work=Pure People|language=fr|quote=Apr\u00e8s sa tourn\u00e9e solo, il retrouvera son groupe pour enregistrer le quatri\u00e8me album des Strokes.}}</ref>\n\nCasablancas composed an original song, \"I Like The Night\", as part of his endorsement deal to represent Azzaro's new men's fragrance, Decibel, dB. The Azzaro Decibel television commercial featuring Julian aired in France on September 1, 2011.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/strokes-frontman-julian-casablancas-stars-230304|title=Strokes Frontman Julian Casablancas Stars in a New Perfume Ad|last=Schutte|first=Lauren|date=September 1, 2011|access-date=September 20, 2011|publisher=Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>\n\nCasablancas also hosted a monthly music show ''Culture Void'' on [[SiriusXMU|Sirius XMU]] between May 2016 and February 2017, where the singer curated and shared some music across genres.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/65684-julian-casablancas-to-host-sirius-xm-show/|title=Julian Casablancas to Host Sirius XM Show|last=Gordon|first=Jeremy|date=May 24, 2016|website=Pitchfork|language=en}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n=== The Voidz (2013\u2013present) ===\n{{Main|The Voidz}}\n[[File:Julian Casablancas + The Voidz.jpg|thumb|300px|Julian Casablancas + The Voidz performing at The Coronet, 2014]]\nCasablancas' most recent project of focus, The Voidz, formerly known as Julian Casablancas + The Voidz, was formed in 2013. Along with Casablancas as lead vocalist, the band consists of Jeramy \"Beardo\" Gritter and Amir Yaghmai on guitar, Jacob \"Jake\" Bercovici on bass (as well as synthesizer), Alex Carapetis on drums and percussion, and Jeff Kite on keyboard.<ref>{{Citation|title=The Voidz|date=2018-09-03|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=The_Voidz&oldid=857907197|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2018-11-06}}</ref> Wanting to earn a greater sense of respect as a band, rather than be perceived as a \u201cside-project\u201d of Julian's, the band officially changed their name from \"Julian Casablancas + The Voidz\" to simply \"The Voidz\" during an 'initiation' video on the band's YouTube page on December 8, 2017.<ref>{{Citation|last=The Voidz|title=The Voidz \"initiate\" Julian (band name change/album announce)|date=December 8, 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oQx3h5D9pwg|accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.self-titledmag.com/2018/10/04/the-voidz-feature-interview/|title=Enter The Voidz|date=2018-10-04|work=self-titled|access-date=2018-11-06|language=en-US}}</ref> Julian performed with Carapetis and Kite throughout the tour for his solo album, ''Phrazes for the Young''. Through Carapetis, Casablancas met Gritter and Bercovici. Bercovici, having played music with Yaghmai for several of years, then connected him to Casablancas, forming what is now known as The Voidz.<ref>{{Citation|last=CultRecordsNYC|title=\"Can I VHS you?\" - Julian Casablancas+The Voidz interview|date=2014-03-25|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yv2sIM-BwdM|access-date=2018-11-06}}</ref>\n\nThough the band's sound has not always been well received, The Voidz aim to \u201cbridge the gap\u201d between music that is both aggressive and complex.<ref name=\":1\">{{Citation|last=Yanina Sep\u00falveda Villablanca|title=Julian Casablancas Interview - Lollapalooza Chile 2014|date=2014-06-09|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YBYQsRFlY2E|access-date=2018-11-08}}</ref> They share the goal of \u201crepresenting things unseen\u201d and \"exploring [music] from the margins\u201d, as Jake [Bercovici] has said.<ref name=\":0\">{{Citation|last=Lau GenteSexy|title=The Voidz Live on KCRW - New album Virtue - April 2, 2018|date=2018-04-02|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZcjvG5QsH6Y|access-date=2018-11-08}}</ref> Inspired by the complex nature of Middle Eastern music scales, Casablancas claims to be more interested in \u201cthe in between notes\u201d than the traditional 7 note scale of Western music.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/03/julian-casablancas-in-conversation.html|title=Julian Casablancas on His Album, the Strokes, and How Money Ruined Modern Pop|last=Marchese|first=David|work=Vulture|access-date=2018-11-08|language=en}}</ref> The band is bound by a mutual love for powerful music that does not gain much attention in mainstream media, which is embodied in Julian's record company, Cult Records, as well.<ref name=\":0\" /> Julian claims that his work with The Voidz is simply an \u201cevolution of the same mission\u201d [as with The Strokes],<ref name=\":3\">{{Citation|last=Redacted Tonight|title=[127] Politics In Music w/ Julian Casablancas|date=2018-09-27|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=94hM2wkA1mw&t=1010s|access-date=2018-11-09}}</ref> but The Voidz are more aligned with the type of music with which he would like to experiment, moving forward.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/five-wild-moments-from-our-julian-casablancas-interview-127152/|title=Five Wild Moments From Our Julian Casablancas Interview|date=2018-03-13|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=2018-11-09|language=en-US}}</ref> Though the Voidz remain a more active musical entity, both bands are still currently represented under Cult Records.\n\nIn June 2014, Casablancas announced he would be releasing the debut album, ''[[Tyranny (Julian Casablancas+The Voidz album)|Tyranny]].'' The album would be released on his own label, Cult Records<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/julian-casablancas-and-the-voidz-set-tyranny-release-date-20140623|title=Julian Casablancas and the Voidz Plan New Album 'Tyranny'|last=Nick Murray|date=June 23, 2014|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=December 11, 2013}}</ref> and coincided with his move to Upstate New York.<ref name=\"save you\" /> On September 23, 2014, the album was released, followed by a tour in the United States and United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://maybeyoulivetwice.noisey.com/|title=Maybe You Live Twice: Julian Casablancas's New Void|access-date=October 25, 2017}}</ref> The album features the 11-minute single \"Human Sadness\", a song whose demo was originally composed for the soundtrack of ''The Unseen Beauty'', a short documentary film which profiled Casablancas' stepfather, artist Sam Adoquei.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cultrecords.com/news/the-unseen-beauty-documentary/|title=The Unseen Beauty Documentary|work=Cult Records}}</ref> The group revealed dates for a South American tour in August 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/7942382/julian-casablancas-the-voidz-south-american-tour-dates|title=Julian Casablancas + The Voidz Announce South American Tour|work=Billboard|access-date=October 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, 2018, The Voidz released their second album, titled ''Virtue''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://juliancasablancas.com/voidz-virtue-pre-order/|title=The Voidz \u2018Virtue\u2019 out March 30 {{!}} Julian Casablancas|website=juliancasablancas.com|access-date=2018-11-06}}</ref> The album takes on a more political stance, dissecting universal concepts such as the paradox between what is perceived as \u201ctruth\u201d and \u201clies\u201d, when taking multiple perceptual view points into consideration.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2018/04/the-voidz-dont-give-a-fuck-what-you-think/|title=The Voidz Don\u2019t Give a Fuck What You Think|date=2018-04-02|work=Consequence of Sound|access-date=2018-11-06|language=en-US}}</ref> The album features track, \u201cPyramid of Bones\u201d, which was featured on Adult Swim in April 2018, along with their single \u201cCoul as a Ghoul\u201d on the Adult Swim's Singles Program.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/Casablancas_J/status/985350340898885633|title=Julian Casablancas on Twitter|work=Twitter|access-date=2018-11-06|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.spin.com/2018/04/the-voidz-coul-as-a-ghuol-adult-swim/|title=Listen to The Voidz\u2019s New Adult Swim Single \"Coul as a Ghoul\"|date=2018-04-18|work=Spin|access-date=2018-11-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Collaborations ===\nCasablancas, along with the Strokes, provided vocals on a cover of [[Marvin Gaye]]'s \"[[Mercy Mercy Me (The Ecology)]]\" with [[Joshua Homme]] on drums and [[Eddie Vedder]] on backup vocals. The cover was released in 2006 as the B-side to \"[[You Only Live Once (The Strokes song)|You Only Live Once]]\". Casablancas also provided bass guitar and backing vocals on [[Albert Hammond, Jr.'s]] \"Scared\" on his solo album ''[[Yours to Keep (Albert Hammond Jr. album)|Yours to Keep]]''. He subsequently played a [[Guitar synthesizer|Casio guitar]] and provided backing vocals on \"[[Sick, Sick, Sick]]\" by [[Queens of the Stone Age]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shesfixingherhair.co.uk/blog/interviews/interviews-nme-december-2005|title=NME Track by Track by The Strokes|date=December 2005|website=shesfixingherhair.co.uk|publisher=NME|accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, he recorded a song with [[Santigold]] (then known as Santogold) and [[Pharrell]] of [[N*E*R*D]] called \"[[My Drive Thru]]\" for a [[Converse (shoe company)|Converse]] advertising campaign.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://americansongwriter.com/2008/07/pharrell-casablancas-santogold-record-song/|title=Pharrell, Casablancas, Santogold Record Song \u00ab American Songwriter|last=McKenna|first=Brittney|date=July 11, 2008|work=American Songwriter|language=en-US}}</ref> During his solo phase, he recorded \"[[Boombox (The Lonely Island song)|Boombox]]\" with [[Andy Samberg]], [[Jorma Taccone]], and [[Akiva Schaffer]] of [[The Lonely Island]] for their 2009 debut album ''[[Incredibad]]'', and was featured in an [[SNL Digital Short]] for the same song.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/38187-watch-the-lonely-islandjulian-casablancas-boombox-video/ |title=Watch the Lonely Island/Julian Casablancas \"Boombox\" Video |last=Breihan |first=Tom |date=March 15, 2010 |website=Pitchfork |language=en |access-date=October 25, 2017}}</ref> In addition, he also recorded \"I Wish It Was Christmas Today\", a festive song based on a ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' skit made popular by [[Jimmy Fallon]], [[Horatio Sanz]], [[Chris Kattan]] and [[Tracy Morgan]]. Casablancas performed the song live on ''[[Late Night with Jimmy Fallon]]'' on December 21, 2009, together with [[The Roots]], Horatio Sanz and Jimmy Fallon. He also appeared in the 100th Digital Short, which aired on May 12, 2012.\nCasablancas also collaborated with [[Danger Mouse (music producer)|Danger Mouse]] and [[Sparklehorse]] on the song \"Little Girl\" on the 2010 album, ''[[Dark Night of the Soul (album)|Dark Night of the Soul]]'', contributing the lyrics, lead and backing vocals, and guitar solo.<ref>{{cite news |title=Danger Mouse And Sparklehorse \u2013 Dark Night Of The Soul |url=http://www.discogs.com/Danger-Mouse-And-Sparklehorse-Dark-Night-Of-The-Soul/release/2364840 |publisher=Discogs.com |accessdate=June 8, 2012}}</ref> Aside from vocal collaborations, he also contributed to a song, \"Forrest Gump\", on [[Digitalism (band)|Digitalism]]'s sophomore album ''[[I Love You Dude|I Love You, Dude]]'' in 2011. The [[electronica]] duo initiated a collaboration with Casablancas through his manager, and Casablancas contributed 'a 30-second recording with him on guitar' via email.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/friends-in-high-places-20110709-1h7ej.html#ixzz1RcUSsRdQ |title=Friends in high places |date=July 10, 2011 |access-date=September 20, 2011 |publisher=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\n\nCasablancas also lent his vocals to the title track, \"Rave On\", on a 2011 tribute album to [[Buddy Holly]], ''[[Rave On Buddy Holly]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/julian_casablancas-rave_on_buddy_holly_cover|title=Julian Casablancas 'Rave On' (Buddy Holly cover)|last=Hughes|first=Josiah|date=May 15, 2011|work=Exclaim!|language=en}}</ref> In 2016, Casablancas contributed three specially recorded [[The Velvet Underground]] and [[Lou Reed]] covers \u2013 ''[[Venus in Furs (song)|Venus in Furs]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pdUrmNKc7uU|title=Julian Casablancas \"Venus In Furs\" [Official Audio]|website=YouTube|accessdate=April 29, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Run Run Run (The Velvet Underground song)|Run Run Run]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mc-MliXZrlU|title=Julian Casablancas - Run Run Run [Official Audio]|website=YouTube|accessdate=April 29, 2016}}</ref> and ''[[White Light/White Heat (song)|White Light/White Heat]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JpWz_CdXCNU|title=Julian Casablancas \"White Light White Heat (rock n roll animal live era version)\" [Official Audio]|website=YouTube|accessdate=April 29, 2016}}</ref> under the title ''White Light White Heat (rock n roll animal live era version)'' \u2013 to the [[HBO]] television series, ''[[Vinyl (TV series)|Vinyl]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/64097-iggy-pop-julian-casablancas-alison-mosshart-the-arcs-release-covers-for-hbos-vinyl/|title=Iggy Pop, Julian Casablancas, Alison Mosshart, the Arcs Release Covers for HBO's \"Vinyl\"|last1=Camp|first1=Zoe|website=Pitchfork|publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast|accessdate=April 29, 2016}}</ref> The songs were subsequently released on various soundtracks to the series by [[Atlantic Records]].\n\nCasablancas worked with [[Daft Punk]] on their 2013 album ''[[Random Access Memories]]'' by contributing lyrics, vocals, and a guitar solo to their song \"[[Instant Crush]]\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2013/04/daft-punk-tease-new-music-at-coachella-featuring-julian-casablancas-and-panda-bear/ |title=Daft Punk tease new music at Coachella, collaborations with Julian Casablancas and Panda Bear |last=Young |first=Alex |date=April 13, 2013 |website=Consequence of Sound |access-date=September 27, 2014}}</ref><ref>Album booklet included with release of ''Random Access Memories'' credits him with words and the guitar solo</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/julian-casablancas-reveals-second-daft-punk-collab-20140331|title=Casablancas Reveals Second Daft Punk Collab|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=October 25, 2017}}</ref> The album won the 2013 [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year]], with Casablancas as one of the co-recipients of the award.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=Julian+Casablancas&field_nominee_work_value=Random+Access+Memories&year=All&genre=All |title=Past Winners Search |date=January 26, 2014 |publisher=grammy.com |access-date=January 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, it was revealed that Casablancas had worked on a song with [[Savages (band)|Savages]]' [[Camille Berthomier|Jehnny Beth]]. The collaboration was later announced to be a cover of \"[[Dagger & Guitar#Track listing|Boy/Girl]]\", a 1983 duet by Danish punk band [[Sort Sol]] and [[Lydia Lunch]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/1845956/julian-casablancas-jehnny-beth-collaboration-is-a-dutch-punk-cover-out-next-month/news/|title=Julian Casablancas & Jehnny Beth Collaboration Is A Danish Punk Cover Out Next Month|last1=DeVille|first1=Chris|website=Stereogum|accessdate=December 10, 2015}}</ref> The music video, directed by [[Warren Fu]], was released on December 4, 2015. The 7\" was released through both Cult Records and Pop Noire Records on December 18, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/59377-julian-casablancas-and-savages-jehnny-beth-cover-sort-sol-and-lydia-lunchs-boygirl/|title=Julian Casablancas and Savages' Jehnny Beth Cover Sort Sol and Lydia Lunch's \"Boy/Girl\"|last1=Beauchemin|first1=Molly|last2=Monroe|first2=Jazz|website=Pitchfork|accessdate=December 10, 2015}}</ref> Casablancas also wrote the song \"Youth Without Love\" for Har Mar Superstar's 2016 album ''Best Summer Ever'',<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bennett|first1=Kim Taylor|title=Har Mar Superstar: \"It Amazes Me How Much People Expect Musicians to be Waifs\"|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/65zanz/har-mar-superstar-best-summer-ever-body-shaming|publisher=Noisey|accessdate=November 1, 2017}}</ref> and is featured on \"No One There\", a song by Indian-born musician, Hammarsing Kharhmar (Exhibition).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/premieres/hear-strokes-julian-casablancas-sing-on-new-exhibition-song-w474907|title=Hear Julian Casablancas Lend Vocals to One of His Favorite New Acts|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=October 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Cult Records ===\nIn 2009, Casablancas founded [[Cult Records]], the creative imprint for his solo album ''[[Phrazes for the Young]]''. The label subsequently signed a partnership agreement with [[Kobalt Label Services]] in 2014, which includes representation and product management, physical distribution across multiple territories, digital distribution through [[AWAL]], marketing and sync licensing services.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stassen|first1=Murray|title=Kobalt Label Services partners with Cult Records|url=http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/kobalt-label-services-partners-with-cult-records/058825|accessdate=November 1, 2017|publisher=Music Week|date=June 25, 2014}}</ref> Cult currently represents [[The Growlers]], [[Har Mar Superstar]], [[Songhoy Blues]], [[Rey Pila]], [[Karen O]], Promiseland, The Strokes, The Voidz, Exhibition and [[Cerebral Ballzy]]. The label has also released works of Albert Hammond Jr., [[The Virgins]], Reputante, INHEAVEN, Exclamation Pony and Nelson London (C O L O R).\n\nCasablancas served as a co-producer on Rey Pila's album released on Cult, ''[[The Future Sugar (Rey Pila album)|The Future Sugar]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lange|first1=Maggie|title=Let Julian Casablancas' New Favorite Band Rey Pila Electrify Your Evening|url=https://www.gq.com/story/rey-pila-julian-casablancas-future-sugar|accessdate=November 1, 2017|publisher=GQ|date=September 24, 2015}}</ref> In August 2016, Cult Records announced a new album with [[The Growlers]], a Southern California-based band. It was also announced that Casablancas himself was producing the album, later known as ''[[City Club (album)|City Club]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2016/07/cult-records-announces-new-growlers-album-fall-tou.html|title=Cult Records Announces New Growlers Album, Fall Tour|access-date=August 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Musical influences ==\n[[File:Lou Reed (5900407225).jpg|thumb|200px|right|Casablancas recognized [[Lou Reed]] as a key influence on his musical style]]\nCasablancas claims that one of his earliest musical influences was [[The Doors]]- musically and instrumentally, in particular, rather than through the identity of [[Jim Morrison]] as a frontman.<ref name=\":4\" /> He has also cited [[Lou Reed]] of [[The Velvet Underground]] as a major influence on his lyrics and singing style. \"The way Lou Reed wrote and sang about drugs and sex, about the people around him \u2014 it was so matter-of-fact,\" Casablancas stated in a ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' interview. \"Reed could be romantic in the way he portrayed these crazy situations, but he was also intensely real. It was poetry and journalism.\"\n\nAdditionally, he has stated that [[Bob Marley]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americansongwriter.com/2010/08/drinks-with-julian-casablancas/|title=Drinks With: Julian Casablancas|last=Matheny|first=Skip|date=August 2, 2010|website=American Songwriter|publisher=AmericanSongwriter.com|accessdate=September 18, 2011}}</ref> [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] and [[Pearl Jam]] are major influences on his work, the latter being the reason he started making music, upon hearing the song \"[[Yellow Ledbetter]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/the-strokes-elegantly-wasted-20031113|title=The Strokes: Elegantly Wasted|last=Strauss|first=Neil|date=November 13, 2003|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=September 27, 2014}}</ref> Julian, in agreement with several members of The Voidz, has named [[Stevie Wonder]] as being a composer with a \u201cnext level mind\".<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Personal life ==\nJulian Casablancas has several half-siblings, including an elder sister, Cecile Casablancas, from his father's first marriage,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://people.com/archive/someone-old-someone-new-vol-39-no-10/|title=Someone Old, Someone New \u2013 Vol. 39 No. 10|date=March 15, 1999|work=PEOPLE|language=en-US}}</ref> and three other siblings from the third marriage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/21/nyregion/john-casablancas-modeling-visionary-dies-at-70.html|title=John Casablancas, Modeling Visionary, Dies at 70|last=Wilson|first=Eric|date=July 20, 2013|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, he married Juliet Joslin, who was the assistant manager of The Strokes at the time.<ref name=\"save you\" /> Their son, Cal, was born in January 2010.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cleveland.com/popmusic/index.ssf/2010/04/for_julian_casablancas_life_go.html|title=For Julian Casablancas, life goes on without the Strokes|last=Soeder|first=John|date=April 1, 2010|work=The Plain Dealer|access-date=November 1, 2017|language=en-US|quote=Casablancas said of his son, Cal, born in January}}</ref> Their second son, Zephyr, was born March 27, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chatting with Julian Casablancas|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pUmuytn_Wao|website=YouTube|accessdate=28 March 2018}}</ref> They divorced in 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-strokes-brooklyn-bridge-to-chorus-978812/|title=The Strokes Go New Wave on Latest Single \u2018Brooklyn Bridge to Chorus|last=Shaffer|first=Claire|date=April 6, 2020|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=April 6, 2020|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nHe has maintained a sober lifestyle since 2009.<ref>{{cite web|author=David Renshaw Oct 18, 2014 12:40 pm BST |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/julian-casablancas-21-1237616 |title=Julian Casablancas: 'I was hungover for five years' |publisher=NME |date=2014-10-18 |accessdate=2019-06-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Patrick Doyle |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/22-things-you-learn-hanging-out-with-julian-casablancas-190764/ |title=22 Things You Learn Hanging Out With Julian Casablancas |work=Rolling Stone |date=2014-10-28 |accessdate=2019-06-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Power |first=Ed |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/the-growing-pains-of-julian-casablancas-1813477.html |title=The growing pains of Julian Casablancas |publisher=The Independent |date=2009-11-02 |accessdate=2019-06-20}}</ref>\n\n=== Politics ===\nIn recent years, Julian has become increasingly more vocal about his political interests, and has concluded that there is a direct parallel between politics and music.<ref name=\":2\" /> Though he claims the reelection of [[George W. Bush]] was the catalyst for his political intrigue, this link between political thought and music became much more evident upon the 2018 release of The Voidz\u2019 album, ''Virtue,'' through which he more explicitly expresses politically-charged ideas.<ref name=\":3\" /> Doing so, Casablancas explains, is using his music as a \u201cmeans to an end to make the world a better place.\u201d<ref name=\":3\" /> The music industry, according to Casablancas, operates quite similarly to the political world, where \u201cwhoever\u2019s propaganda\u2019s the loudest\u201d is what is popular, regardless of its quality.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 2016 Casablancas interviewed [[Henry Giroux]], during which they discuss the idea of whether or not the average American identifies that there are still existing struggles and conflicts that need to be addressed within the country.<ref>{{Citation|last=Rolling Stone|title=Julian Casablancas Interviews Henry Giroux|date=2016-09-13|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hLRWPsIzSOo&list=RD94hM2wkA1mw&index=3|access-date=2018-11-15}}</ref> Amongst various other issues impending on society today, Casablancas is most concerned with the idea that institutions have become more powerful than democratic government.<ref name=\":3\" /> He proposes that there is a perpetual conflict between those who understand that the democratic nature of the U.S. is lost and those who seek to keep it that way.<ref name=\":3\" /> It is in this way that the music industry reflects the nature of politics- quality and integrity is compromised under the control of capitalist greed.\n\nCasablancas cites some of his most politically influential figures as [[Oliver Stone]], [[Chris Hedges]], [[Jesse Ventura]], and [[Howard Zinn]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> He notes [[Martin Luther King Jr.]] as his favorite philosopher, whose work, Casablancas claims, held truth as an important standard value.<ref name=\":3\" /> He recognizes [[Paul Robeson]] as someone who used his musical platform to help further his serious political intrigue and as someone who, therefore, serves as a role model for politically engaged musicians.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nCasablancas has been a guest on ''[[Redacted Tonight]]'', as well as included its host, Lee Camp, as an opener for a Voidz show in Houston, Texas in October 2018.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nCasablancas endorsed Senator [[Bernie Sanders]] for the [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries]], and performed with his band at a rally in the [[University of New Hampshire]] the night before the New Hampshire primary.<ref> {{url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/01/the-strokes-bernie-sanders-rally-in-new-hampshire/}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy and influence ==\n[[Courtney Love]]'s song \"But Julian, I'm a Little Bit Older Than You\", from her debut solo album ''[[America's Sweetheart (album)|America's Sweetheart]]'' (2004), was written about Julian Casablancas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/courtney-love/5806|title=Courtney Love : California Ventura Theatre on|date=November 6, 2001|publisher=Nme.com|accessdate=March 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe has also served as inspiration for several other musicians including [[Alex Turner]] of the [[Arctic Monkeys]] and the painter [[Elizabeth Peyton]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.artnet.fr/artistes/elizabeth-peyton/julian-a-ewh86UBWVWlrs8DPiRN0rw2 |title=Elizabeth Peyton \u2013 Julian |publisher=Artnet.fr |access-date=March 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n'''Solo'''\n{{Main|Julian Casablancas discography}}\n* ''[[Phrazes for the Young]]'' (2009)\n\n\n'''The Strokes'''\n{{main|The Strokes discography}}\n* ''[[Is This It]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Room on Fire]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[First Impressions of Earth]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Angles (The Strokes album)|Angles]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Comedown Machine]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[The New Abnormal]]'' (2020)\n\n\n'''The Voidz'''\n{{main|The Voidz discography}}\n* ''[[Tyranny (The Voidz album)|Tyranny]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Virtue (The Voidz album)|Virtue]]'' (2018)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Julian Casablancas}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Julian Casablancas}}\n* {{Official website|http://juliancasablancas.com/main/}}\n\n{{Julian Casablancas}}\n{{The Strokes}}\n{{The Voidz}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Casablancas, Julian}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Institut Le Rosey]]\n[[Category:American baritones]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American rock singers]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American rock songwriters]]\n[[Category:American male songwriters]]\n[[Category:American people of Catalan descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Danish descent]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Singers from New York City]]\n[[Category:The Strokes members]]\n[[Category:Lyc\u00e9e Fran\u00e7ais de New York alumni]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Julian Casablancas\n| image              = [[File:Julian Casablancas @ Lollapalooza 2014 (13657827913).jpg|center|250px]]\n| caption            = Casablancas performing at Lollapalooza 2014\n| birth_name         = Julian Fernando Casablancas\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1978|8|23}}\n| birth_place        = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Singer|musician|songwriter|record producer}}\n| years_active       = 1998\u2013present\n| relatives          = [[John Casablancas]] (father)\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Juliet Joslin|2005|2019|end=div}}\n| children           = 2\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background = solo_singer\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Indie rock]]|[[alternative rock]]|[[garage rock revival]]|[[New wave music|new wave]]|[[experimental rock]]}}\n| instrument = {{hlist|Vocals|guitar|keyboards|drums|bass guitar}}\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Cult Records|Cult]]|[[Rough Trade Records|Rough Trade]]|[[RCA Records|RCA]]}}\n| associated_acts = {{hlist|[[The Strokes]]|[[Julian Casablancas+The Voidz|The Voidz]]|[[Albert Hammond Jr.]]|[[The Growlers]]|[[Daft Punk]]|[[Queens of the Stone Age]]}}\n| website    = {{URL|juliancasablancas.com}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Julian Fernando Casablancas''' (born August 23, 1978) is an American singer, musician, songwriter, and record producer. He is best known as the lead singer and primary songwriter of American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[The Strokes]].\n\nIn 2009, Casablancas released a solo album, ''[[Phrazes for the Young]]'', and in 2013 he formed [[experimental rock]] outfit Julian Casablancas + The Voidz, now known simply as [[The Voidz]], with whom he has released two albums: ''[[Tyranny (The Voidz album)|Tyranny]]'' (2014) and ''[[Virtue (The Voidz album)|Virtue]]'' (2018).\n\nAlso in 2009, Casablancas founded [[independent record label]] [[Cult Records]],<ref>Blistein, Jon.[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/julian-casablancas-previews-new-album-with-rioters-and-video-games-20140306 Julian Casablancas Previews New Album With Rioters and Video Games\"] ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' March 6, 2014.</ref> which currently represents artists such as [[The Growlers]], [[Rey Pila]], and [[Karen O]].<ref>[http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/kobalt-label-services-partners-with-cult-records/058825 Kobalt Label Services partners with Cult Records]. June 25, 2014</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nJulian Fernando Casablancas was born in [[New York City]] on August 23, 1978,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themodernage.co.uk/julianx.html|title=Julian Casablancas profile|publisher=themodernage.co.uk|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071122004758/http://www.themodernage.co.uk/julianx.html|archivedate=November 22, 2007|url-status=dead|accessdate=August 9, 2011}}</ref> the son of American business mogul [[John Casablancas]], best known as the founder of [[Elite Model Management]], and Danish former model Jeanette Christiansen, who was crowned the 1965 [[Miss Universe Denmark|Miss Denmark]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VeUCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA38|title=Girl Crazy|last=Prince|first=Dinah|date=January 25, 1988|work=New York Magazine|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=38|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2013/jul/24/john-casablancas|title=John Casablancas obituary|last=Horwell|first=Veronica|date=July 24, 2013|work=The Guardian|access-date=October 25, 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> He has [[Catalans|Catalan]] ancestry on his father's side. When Casablancas was eight, his parents divorced. He once stated that he wanted to be closer to his father, and this \"translated into teenage rebelliousness\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/julian-casablancas-radical-reinvention-20141015|title=Julian Casablancas' Radical Reinvention|last=Doyle|first=Patrick|date=October 15, 2014|work=Rolling Stone}}</ref> His mother subsequently married painter Sam Adoquei.<ref name=\"save you\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.gq.com/story/julian-casablancas |title=Julian Casablancas Is Done Trying to Save You |last=Davidson |first=Zach Baron, Eric Ray |date=September 18, 2014 |work=GQ |access-date=October 25, 2017 |language=en}}</ref> Adoquei helped shape Casablancas' early musical taste by exposing him to music such as [[The Doors]], which was markedly different from the mostly [[Phil Collins]]-influenced music he listened to as a child.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/oct/04/julian-casablancas-strokes-interview |title=Julian Casablancas: 'Does my mind just go blank? Yeah, all the time' |last=Wood |first=Gaby |date=October 3, 2009 |work=The Guardian |access-date=October 25, 2017 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nCasablancas has known the bassist of The Strokes, [[Nikolai Fraiture]], since they were six,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/the-making-of-the-strokes-20020411|title=The Making of the Strokes|last=Eliscu|first=Jenny|date=April 11, 2002|work=Rolling Stone}}</ref> while both were attending [[Lyc\u00e9e Fran\u00e7ais de New York]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lfnyalumni.org/en/classmate/classmateresults/classmateresults.php?criteria=1997 |title=AALFNY: Find a Classmate |publisher=Lfnyalumni.org |date= |accessdate=March 20, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lfnyalumni.org/en/classmate/classmateresults/classmateresults.php?criteria=1996 |title=AALFNY: Find a Classmate |publisher=Lfnyalumni.org |date=January 26, 2009 |accessdate=March 20, 2011}}</ref> When he was 13, Casablancas' father sent him to [[Institut Le Rosey]], a boarding school in [[Switzerland]], where he met future Strokes member [[Albert Hammond, Jr.|Albert Hammond Jr.]]<ref name=\"jimdero1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.jimdero.com/OtherWritings/OtherStrokes.htm|title=The Strokes|last=DeRogatis|first=Jim|date=November 2001|website=Jimdero.com|publisher=Penthouse|access-date=March 20, 2011}}</ref> Casablancas later returned to New York and attended [[Dwight School]] with two other future Strokes, [[Nick Valensi]] and [[Fabrizio Moretti]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://issuu.com/thedwightschool/docs/dwight_1995_reduced/105|title=Dwight 1995|work=Issuu|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"jimdero1\" /> Casablancas never finished high school, but took a [[General Educational Development|GED]] and continued to take music classes at [[Five Towns College]], where he says he first enjoyed himself in class.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NG1PsNK2_Bw |title=Road Tripping with Julian Casablancas |website=YouTube |publisher=BBC Radio |access-date=July 5, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2003/oct/31/2?INTCMP=SRCH | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Neil | last=Strauss | title=Neil Strauss spends seven days with the Strokes | date=October 31, 2003}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=deD1CQAAQBAJ|title=Meet Me in the Bathroom: Rebirth and Rock and Roll in New York City 2001-2011|last=Goodman|first=Lizzy|date=May 23, 2017|publisher=HarperCollins|year=|isbn=9780062233127|location=|pages=|language=en|quote=I left and got a GED and went to Five Towns, which is a vocational music school that anyone can go to.}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== The Strokes (1998\u2013present) ===\n{{Main|The Strokes}}\n[[File:The Strokes by Roger Woolman.jpg|thumb|left|Casablancas with the Strokes in 2002]]\nUpon meeting future guitarist [[Nick Valensi]] and drummer [[Fabrizio Moretti|Fab Moretti]] at Dwight School in Manhattan, the three began to play music together. He reconnected with guitarist [[Albert Hammond Jr.|Albert Hammond Jr]]. when the latter moved to New York. The band was formed in 1998 when Hammond was accepted into the band,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/feb/27/the-strokes-angles-casablancas-interview|title=The Strokes: 'All that Spinal Tap bullshit has gone out the window'|last=Hoby|first=Hermione|date=February 27, 2011|work=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref> with Casablancas as the lead vocalist and main songwriter and Nikolai Fraiture on bass.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=crQoYila-dAC&pg=PA74&lpg=PA74|title=Gang of Five|last=Klosterman|first=Chuck|date=December 2003|publisher=Spin|isbn=|location=|pages=74|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe band began rehearsing a fourteen-song set which included \"Alone, Together\", \"Barely Legal\", \"[[Last Nite]]\", \"[[The Modern Age]]\", \"New York City Cops\", \"Soma\", \"Someday\", \"Take It or Leave It\" and \"This Life\" (an early version of \"Trying Your Luck\"). Most of these songs now feature different lyrics. A demo sent to the newly reformed [[Rough Trade Records]] in the UK sparked interest there, leading to their first release via the website of the UK magazine, ''[[NME]],'' who gave away a free mp3 download of \"[[Last Nite]]\" a week prior to the physical release as part of ''[[The Modern Age]] EP'' in 2001. The EP sparked a bidding war among record labels, the largest for a rock and roll band in years. Shortly after, The Strokes' critically acclaimed debut album ''[[Is This It]]'' was released.\n\nThe band has received the highest of praise for ''Is This It,'' and it set the stage for what people expected to \u201csave rock\u201d in the new millennium.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gq.com/story/the-strokes-retrospective|title=The Fifteen-Year Decline of the Strokes|last=Nguyen|first=Kevin|date=2016-08-12|work=GQ|access-date=2018-11-30|language=en}}</ref> Though some would argue that such statements left unreasonably sized shoes to fill, The Strokes are still highly recognized as one of the most influential garage rock bands of the early 2000s, paving the way for many new alternative bands to come.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2017/05/26/how-the-strokes-helped-make-nyc-the-worlds-sexy-rock-capital/|title=The inside story of the band that defined the 2000s|date=2017-05-26|work=New York Post|access-date=2018-11-30|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nStatistically, all albums released following their debut were not nearly as successful or well-received by fans and critics.<ref>{{Citation|title=The Strokes|date=2018-11-15|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=The_Strokes&oldid=868990975|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2018-11-30}}</ref> In an excerpt from Lizzie Goodman's ''Meet Me in the Bathroom: Rebirth and Rock and Roll in New York City, 2001-2011-'' named after The Strokes' track- Strokes guitarist, Nick Valensi, comments, ''\"''With ''[[Room on Fire]]'' [2003], people were giving us shit because they said we were sounding too much the same. With the third album [''[[First Impressions of Earth]]''], we were getting shit that we don\u2019t sound like ''Room on Fire''. We got fucked by the same thing twice!\"<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.vulture.com/2017/05/the-strokes-an-oral-history.html|title=How the Strokes \u2014 and the Early-Aughts New York Rock Boom \u2014 Went Bust|last=Goodman|first=Lizzy|work=Vulture|access-date=2018-11-30|language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[File:StrokesBrooklyn311219-237.jpg|thumb|right|Casablancas performing with the Strokes on New Year's Eve 2019]]\n\nAfter the release of the two other albums and several major tours, the band took a 5-year break before returning with their fourth album [[Angles (The Strokes album)|''Angles'']] in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/article/7925-this-is-it-ten-years-of-the-strokes/|title=This Is It: Ten Years of the Strokes|last=Garrett|first=Jonathan|date=March 7, 2011|website=Pitchfork|language=en}}</ref> The five-year hiatus was said to be the result of conflicting solo projects, sobriety issues, and unspoken emotions.The Strokes' drummer Fab Moretti claimed the band struggled to process such \"subconscious volcanic emotions\", partly because they were still \"children\" at the time.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nThough their creative processes has been critiqued by outside observers as \u201ca democracy under a dictator\u201d,<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/nymetro/news/culture/features/15495/index6.html|title=Group Therapy|website=NYMag.com|access-date=2018-11-26}}</ref> Casablancas has encouraged each band member to contribute their own ideas and collectively sort through which ones will potentially turn into something more.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.clashmusic.com/features/julian-casablancas-interview|title=Julian Casablancas Interview|work=Clash Magazine|access-date=2018-11-30|language=en}}</ref> Commenting on the meticulous nature of Julian's creative process, guitarist, Nick Valensi, has said, \u201chis ear is so sharp. He\u2019s the one with the ear for detail in this band. Creatively, he is a force to be reckoned with.\u201d<ref name=\":6\" /> The 2011 release, ''Angles,'' is said to reflect the beginning of the more collaborative nature of the band's creative process.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/13/arts/music/the-strokes-embrace-group-dynamics-in-a-new-album.html|title=The Strokes Embrace Group Dynamics in a New Album|last=Ryzik|first=Melena|access-date=2018-11-30|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe album release was followed by several headlining appearances at musical festivals, including Reading, Coachella, Lollapalooza and Austin City Limits.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/q-a-julian-casablancas-on-his-solo-album-and-the-strokes-return-20100819 |title=Q&A: Julian Casablancas on His Solo Album and the Strokes' Return |last=Hiatt |first=Brian |date= August 19, 2010 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=October 25, 2017}}</ref> The band released ''[[Comedown Machine]]'' in 2013, as their last album under the contract with long-time label [[RCA Records|RCA]], for which they did no promotion.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://entertainment.time.com/2013/03/26/the-strokes-wipe-the-slate-clean-on-comedown-machine/|title=The Strokes Wipe the Slate Clean on Comedown Machine|last=Roffman|first=Michael|work=Time|access-date=October 25, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0040-781X}}</ref> The band released an EP, ''[[Future Present Past]]'', on Casablancas' own label Cult Records in 2016.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/the-strokes-preview-future-present-past-ep-with-new-song-oblivius-20160526 |title=Strokes Preview New EP With Blistering New Songs |last=Blistein |first=Jon |date=May 26, 2016 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=October 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, it was announced that the band would headline at [[Bilbao BBK Live]] in 2019, kicking off their global comeback.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2018/12/the-strokes-global-comeback-2019/|title=The Strokes plotting \"global comeback\" for 2019|date=2018-12-17|website=Consequence of Sound|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> Numerous dates for festivals and shows have been announced afterwards, including a show at the [[Governors Ball Music Festival]], marking the band's return to New York City.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/governors-ball-2019-lineup-announced-the-strokes-tyler-lil-wayne-sza-more/|title=Governors Ball 2019 Lineup Announced: The Strokes, Tyler, Lil Wayne, SZA, More|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref>\n\nStarting May 14, 2019, The Strokes teased some of new songs, starting with \"The Adults are Talking\", live at [[Pellissier Building and Wiltern Theatre|The Wiltern]] in Los Angeles, giving remarks that there is possibilities for the Strokes to release a new album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-strokes-the-adults-are-talking-live-835099/|title=Watch The Strokes Debut New Song 'The Adults Are Talking'|last=Zemler|first=Emily|last2=Zemler|first2=Emily|date=2019-05-14|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> In December 31, 2019 at Brooklyn NYE, they performed \"Ode to the Mets\", as an offer from Casablancas to sing live instead of singing songs from ''Angles'' as requested by fans. \u201cI don\u2019t remember ''Angles''. What\u2019s ''Angles''?\u201d Casablancas responded before suggesting that the band play the new song and later confirming the release of a new project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2020/1/the-strokes-new-album-announcement-ode-to-the-mets-single|title=The Strokes Announce New Album, Debut New Single \"Ode to the Mets\"|website=HYPEBEAST|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, The Strokes released their newest album, ''[[The New Abnormal]]'', which has been receiving positive reviews among critics, where suggesting the band came back with a better maturity and cohesion among bandmates. The album project was started far back to 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://diymag.com/2016/10/11/the-strokes-new-album-2017-nick-valensi-interview|title=The Strokes are \u201cslowly but surely working on an album\u201d|last=Subscribe|website=diymag.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\n=== Solo projects (2009\u2013present) ===\n[[File:Flickr - moses namkung - Julian Casablancas-2.jpg|thumb|200px|left|Casablancas performing as a solo artist in 2009]]\nAs a solo artist, Casablancas set out with an intention to say what was on his mind, both musically and lyrically.<ref name=\":1\" /> Speaking on his experience as a solo artist versus releasing music with The Strokes, the singer has put it simply, \u201cit\u2019s like touring with me or with five of me,\u201d meaning that each member has their own opinionated state of mind. While such statements raised much concern for the relations between the band members, Casablancas claims that in pursuit of a solo career, he is protecting the integrity of the [Strokes] vibe.<ref>{{Citation|last=Beat Magazine|title=Julian Casablancas Interview|date=2010-05-22|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TRtj6wQngg4&t=400s|access-date=2018-11-09}}</ref> In having a musical project separate from The Strokes, he is able to \u201cchase down any idea [he] wants\u201d, which he would refrain from doing with the band.<ref>{{Citation|last=PerryPoucheen|title=Julian Casablancas - Interview.|date=2011-05-28|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d2ryXJJKXP4&list=PLLZeeZuy6roL7ocqOmOliMSrTX-r3XZCz|access-date=2018-11-09}}</ref>\n\nHis first solo album, ''[[Phrazes for the Young]]'' (inspired by the [[Oscar Wilde]] book \"Phrases and Philosophies for the Use of the Young\"), was released on November 2 in the UK and November 3, 2009, in the United States.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/01/arts/music/01ryzi.html|title=Julian Casablancas, Thriving on Sunshine With a Solo CD|last=Ryzik|first=Melena|date=October 28, 2009|work=The New York Times|access-date=October 25, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Recorded in Omaha, Nebraska, and Casablancas' home city New York, the album was produced by Jason Lader, with additional production from [[Bright Eyes (band)|Bright Eyes]]' [[Mike Mogis]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/the-strokes/46099|title=The Strokes\u2019 Julian Casablancas to release solo album|last=Stokes|first=Paul Stokes|date=July 14, 2009|publisher=NME|access-date=March 20, 2011}}</ref> The album was strongly influenced by [[New wave music|new wave]] and [[electronica]], with Casablancas utilizing [[synthesizer]]s for many songs. He discussed his new influences by saying \"I would've gone weirder with the music, but I wanted to be smart. I didn't want people to say, 'Okay, this is his weird abstract thing,' and dismiss the album. I worked too hard on it for that to happen...I wanted to be crazy original and bridge the gap between traditional music and modern music.\"<ref name=\"SPINterview\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2009/11/spin-interview-julian-casablancas/|title=The SPIN Interview: Julian Casablancas|last=Marchese|first=David|date=October 28, 2009|website=Spin|publisher=Spin Media LLC|access-date=April 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\nJulian Casablancas made his live solo debut for a private party for fashion brand Opening Ceremony in Tokyo, Japan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2009/09/strokes-julian-casablancas-debuts-solo-tunes/|title=Strokes' Julian Casablancas Debuts Solo Tunes|date=September 1, 2009|publisher=Spin.com|access-date=September 18, 2011}}</ref> To celebrate the release of the EP, Casablancas performed a series of shows in October 2009 at The Downtown Palace Theatre in Los Angeles with his live show band, The Sick Six. Members of The Sick Six include [[Jeffrey Kite|Jeff Kite]] (keyboard), Nelson London (synthesizer), JP Bowersock (guitar), [[Danielle Haim]] (percussion) and [[Alex Carapetis]] (drums).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.juliancasablancas.com/news/2010/03/26/id-now-like-to-introduce-the-band|title=I\u2019d Now Like to Introduce the Band|publisher=JulianCasablancas.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402214143/http://www.juliancasablancas.com/news/2010/03/26/id-now-like-to-introduce-the-band|archivedate=April 2, 2012|url-status=dead|accessdate=September 18, 2011}}</ref> Casablancas then toured with The Sick Six in Europe, United States, Australia and Japan from November 2009 until July 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/entertainment/music/frontmans-stroke-of-genius/2010/03/11/1268203345769.html?page=2|title=Frontman's stroke of genius - Music - Entertainment - theage.com.au|date=March 12, 2010|website=The Age|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2010/05/07/music/julians-stroke-of-genius/|title=Julian's stroke of genius|last=Curran|first=Shaun|date=May 7, 2010|work=The Japan Times|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.purepeople.com/article/jamiroquai-phoenix-et-julian-casablancas-la-bretagne-leur-dit-merci_a60183/1|title=Jamiroquai, Phoenix et Julian Casablancas... La Bretagne leur dit merci !|date=July 19, 2010|work=Pure People|language=fr|quote=Apr\u00e8s sa tourn\u00e9e solo, il retrouvera son groupe pour enregistrer le quatri\u00e8me album des Strokes.}}</ref>\n\nCasablancas composed an original song, \"I Like The Night\", as part of his endorsement deal to represent Azzaro's new men's fragrance, Decibel, dB. The Azzaro Decibel television commercial featuring Julian aired in France on September 1, 2011.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/strokes-frontman-julian-casablancas-stars-230304|title=Strokes Frontman Julian Casablancas Stars in a New Perfume Ad|last=Schutte|first=Lauren|date=September 1, 2011|access-date=September 20, 2011|publisher=Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>\n\nCasablancas also hosted a monthly music show ''Culture Void'' on [[SiriusXMU|Sirius XMU]] between May 2016 and February 2017, where the singer curated and shared some music across genres.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/65684-julian-casablancas-to-host-sirius-xm-show/|title=Julian Casablancas to Host Sirius XM Show|last=Gordon|first=Jeremy|date=May 24, 2016|website=Pitchfork|language=en}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n=== The Voidz (2013\u2013present) ===\n{{Main|The Voidz}}\n[[File:Julian Casablancas + The Voidz.jpg|thumb|300px|Julian Casablancas + The Voidz performing at The Coronet, 2014]]\nCasablancas' most recent project of focus, The Voidz, formerly known as Julian Casablancas + The Voidz, was formed in 2013. Along with Casablancas as lead vocalist, the band consists of Jeramy \"Beardo\" Gritter and Amir Yaghmai on guitar, Jacob \"Jake\" Bercovici on bass (as well as synthesizer), Alex Carapetis on drums and percussion, and Jeff Kite on keyboard.<ref>{{Citation|title=The Voidz|date=2018-09-03|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=The_Voidz&oldid=857907197|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2018-11-06}}</ref> Wanting to earn a greater sense of respect as a band, rather than be perceived as a \u201cside-project\u201d of Julian's, the band officially changed their name from \"Julian Casablancas + The Voidz\" to simply \"The Voidz\" during an 'initiation' video on the band's YouTube page on December 8, 2017.<ref>{{Citation|last=The Voidz|title=The Voidz \"initiate\" Julian (band name change/album announce)|date=December 8, 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oQx3h5D9pwg|accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.self-titledmag.com/2018/10/04/the-voidz-feature-interview/|title=Enter The Voidz|date=2018-10-04|work=self-titled|access-date=2018-11-06|language=en-US}}</ref> Julian performed with Carapetis and Kite throughout the tour for his solo album, ''Phrazes for the Young''. Through Carapetis, Casablancas met Gritter and Bercovici. Bercovici, having played music with Yaghmai for several of years, then connected him to Casablancas, forming what is now known as The Voidz.<ref>{{Citation|last=CultRecordsNYC|title=\"Can I VHS you?\" - Julian Casablancas+The Voidz interview|date=2014-03-25|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yv2sIM-BwdM|access-date=2018-11-06}}</ref>\n\nThough the band's sound has not always been well received, The Voidz aim to \u201cbridge the gap\u201d between music that is both aggressive and complex.<ref name=\":1\">{{Citation|last=Yanina Sep\u00falveda Villablanca|title=Julian Casablancas Interview - Lollapalooza Chile 2014|date=2014-06-09|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YBYQsRFlY2E|access-date=2018-11-08}}</ref> They share the goal of \u201crepresenting things unseen\u201d and \"exploring [music] from the margins\u201d, as Jake [Bercovici] has said.<ref name=\":0\">{{Citation|last=Lau GenteSexy|title=The Voidz Live on KCRW - New album Virtue - April 2, 2018|date=2018-04-02|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZcjvG5QsH6Y|access-date=2018-11-08}}</ref> Inspired by the complex nature of Middle Eastern music scales, Casablancas claims to be more interested in \u201cthe in between notes\u201d than the traditional 7 note scale of Western music.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/03/julian-casablancas-in-conversation.html|title=Julian Casablancas on His Album, the Strokes, and How Money Ruined Modern Pop|last=Marchese|first=David|work=Vulture|access-date=2018-11-08|language=en}}</ref> The band is bound by a mutual love for powerful music that does not gain much attention in mainstream media, which is embodied in Julian's record company, Cult Records, as well.<ref name=\":0\" /> Julian claims that his work with The Voidz is simply an \u201cevolution of the same mission\u201d [as with The Strokes],<ref name=\":3\">{{Citation|last=Redacted Tonight|title=[127] Politics In Music w/ Julian Casablancas|date=2018-09-27|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=94hM2wkA1mw&t=1010s|access-date=2018-11-09}}</ref> but The Voidz are more aligned with the type of music with which he would like to experiment, moving forward.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/five-wild-moments-from-our-julian-casablancas-interview-127152/|title=Five Wild Moments From Our Julian Casablancas Interview|date=2018-03-13|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=2018-11-09|language=en-US}}</ref> Though the Voidz remain a more active musical entity, both bands are still currently represented under Cult Records.\n\nIn June 2014, Casablancas announced he would be releasing the debut album, ''[[Tyranny (Julian Casablancas+The Voidz album)|Tyranny]].'' The album would be released on his own label, Cult Records<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/julian-casablancas-and-the-voidz-set-tyranny-release-date-20140623|title=Julian Casablancas and the Voidz Plan New Album 'Tyranny'|last=Nick Murray|date=June 23, 2014|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=December 11, 2013}}</ref> and coincided with his move to Upstate New York.<ref name=\"save you\" /> On September 23, 2014, the album was released, followed by a tour in the United States and United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://maybeyoulivetwice.noisey.com/|title=Maybe You Live Twice: Julian Casablancas's New Void|access-date=October 25, 2017}}</ref> The album features the 11-minute single \"Human Sadness\", a song whose demo was originally composed for the soundtrack of ''The Unseen Beauty'', a short documentary film which profiled Casablancas' stepfather, artist Sam Adoquei.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cultrecords.com/news/the-unseen-beauty-documentary/|title=The Unseen Beauty Documentary|work=Cult Records}}</ref> The group revealed dates for a South American tour in August 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/7942382/julian-casablancas-the-voidz-south-american-tour-dates|title=Julian Casablancas + The Voidz Announce South American Tour|work=Billboard|access-date=October 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, 2018, The Voidz released their second album, titled ''Virtue''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://juliancasablancas.com/voidz-virtue-pre-order/|title=The Voidz \u2018Virtue\u2019 out March 30 {{!}} Julian Casablancas|website=juliancasablancas.com|access-date=2018-11-06}}</ref> The album takes on a more political stance, dissecting universal concepts such as the paradox between what is perceived as \u201ctruth\u201d and \u201clies\u201d, when taking multiple perceptual view points into consideration.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2018/04/the-voidz-dont-give-a-fuck-what-you-think/|title=The Voidz Don\u2019t Give a Fuck What You Think|date=2018-04-02|work=Consequence of Sound|access-date=2018-11-06|language=en-US}}</ref> The album features track, \u201cPyramid of Bones\u201d, which was featured on Adult Swim in April 2018, along with their single \u201cCoul as a Ghoul\u201d on the Adult Swim's Singles Program.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/Casablancas_J/status/985350340898885633|title=Julian Casablancas on Twitter|work=Twitter|access-date=2018-11-06|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.spin.com/2018/04/the-voidz-coul-as-a-ghuol-adult-swim/|title=Listen to The Voidz\u2019s New Adult Swim Single \"Coul as a Ghoul\"|date=2018-04-18|work=Spin|access-date=2018-11-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Collaborations ===\nCasablancas, along with the Strokes, provided vocals on a cover of [[Marvin Gaye]]'s \"[[Mercy Mercy Me (The Ecology)]]\" with [[Joshua Homme]] on drums and [[Eddie Vedder]] on backup vocals. The cover was released in 2006 as the B-side to \"[[You Only Live Once (The Strokes song)|You Only Live Once]]\". Casablancas also provided bass guitar and backing vocals on [[Albert Hammond, Jr.'s]] \"Scared\" on his solo album ''[[Yours to Keep (Albert Hammond Jr. album)|Yours to Keep]]''. He subsequently played a [[Guitar synthesizer|Casio guitar]] and provided backing vocals on \"[[Sick, Sick, Sick]]\" by [[Queens of the Stone Age]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shesfixingherhair.co.uk/blog/interviews/interviews-nme-december-2005|title=NME Track by Track by The Strokes|date=December 2005|website=shesfixingherhair.co.uk|publisher=NME|accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, he recorded a song with [[Santigold]] (then known as Santogold) and [[Pharrell]] of [[N*E*R*D]] called \"[[My Drive Thru]]\" for a [[Converse (shoe company)|Converse]] advertising campaign.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://americansongwriter.com/2008/07/pharrell-casablancas-santogold-record-song/|title=Pharrell, Casablancas, Santogold Record Song \u00ab American Songwriter|last=McKenna|first=Brittney|date=July 11, 2008|work=American Songwriter|language=en-US}}</ref> During his solo phase, he recorded \"[[Boombox (The Lonely Island song)|Boombox]]\" with [[Andy Samberg]], [[Jorma Taccone]], and [[Akiva Schaffer]] of [[The Lonely Island]] for their 2009 debut album ''[[Incredibad]]'', and was featured in an [[SNL Digital Short]] for the same song.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/38187-watch-the-lonely-islandjulian-casablancas-boombox-video/ |title=Watch the Lonely Island/Julian Casablancas \"Boombox\" Video |last=Breihan |first=Tom |date=March 15, 2010 |website=Pitchfork |language=en |access-date=October 25, 2017}}</ref> In addition, he also recorded \"I Wish It Was Christmas Today\", a festive song based on a ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' skit made popular by [[Jimmy Fallon]], [[Horatio Sanz]], [[Chris Kattan]] and [[Tracy Morgan]]. Casablancas performed the song live on ''[[Late Night with Jimmy Fallon]]'' on December 21, 2009, together with [[The Roots]], Horatio Sanz and Jimmy Fallon. He also appeared in the 100th Digital Short, which aired on May 12, 2012.\nCasablancas also collaborated with [[Danger Mouse (music producer)|Danger Mouse]] and [[Sparklehorse]] on the song \"Little Girl\" on the 2010 album, ''[[Dark Night of the Soul (album)|Dark Night of the Soul]]'', contributing the lyrics, lead and backing vocals, and guitar solo.<ref>{{cite news |title=Danger Mouse And Sparklehorse \u2013 Dark Night Of The Soul |url=http://www.discogs.com/Danger-Mouse-And-Sparklehorse-Dark-Night-Of-The-Soul/release/2364840 |publisher=Discogs.com |accessdate=June 8, 2012}}</ref> Aside from vocal collaborations, he also contributed to a song, \"Forrest Gump\", on [[Digitalism (band)|Digitalism]]'s sophomore album ''[[I Love You Dude|I Love You, Dude]]'' in 2011. The [[electronica]] duo initiated a collaboration with Casablancas through his manager, and Casablancas contributed 'a 30-second recording with him on guitar' via email.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/friends-in-high-places-20110709-1h7ej.html#ixzz1RcUSsRdQ |title=Friends in high places |date=July 10, 2011 |access-date=September 20, 2011 |publisher=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\n\nCasablancas also lent his vocals to the title track, \"Rave On\", on a 2011 tribute album to [[Buddy Holly]], ''[[Rave On Buddy Holly]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/julian_casablancas-rave_on_buddy_holly_cover|title=Julian Casablancas 'Rave On' (Buddy Holly cover)|last=Hughes|first=Josiah|date=May 15, 2011|work=Exclaim!|language=en}}</ref> In 2016, Casablancas contributed three specially recorded [[The Velvet Underground]] and [[Lou Reed]] covers \u2013 ''[[Venus in Furs (song)|Venus in Furs]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pdUrmNKc7uU|title=Julian Casablancas \"Venus In Furs\" [Official Audio]|website=YouTube|accessdate=April 29, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Run Run Run (The Velvet Underground song)|Run Run Run]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mc-MliXZrlU|title=Julian Casablancas - Run Run Run [Official Audio]|website=YouTube|accessdate=April 29, 2016}}</ref> and ''[[White Light/White Heat (song)|White Light/White Heat]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JpWz_CdXCNU|title=Julian Casablancas \"White Light White Heat (rock n roll animal live era version)\" [Official Audio]|website=YouTube|accessdate=April 29, 2016}}</ref> under the title ''White Light White Heat (rock n roll animal live era version)'' \u2013 to the [[HBO]] television series, ''[[Vinyl (TV series)|Vinyl]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/64097-iggy-pop-julian-casablancas-alison-mosshart-the-arcs-release-covers-for-hbos-vinyl/|title=Iggy Pop, Julian Casablancas, Alison Mosshart, the Arcs Release Covers for HBO's \"Vinyl\"|last1=Camp|first1=Zoe|website=Pitchfork|publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast|accessdate=April 29, 2016}}</ref> The songs were subsequently released on various soundtracks to the series by [[Atlantic Records]].\n\nCasablancas worked with [[Daft Punk]] on their 2013 album ''[[Random Access Memories]]'' by contributing lyrics, vocals, and a guitar solo to their song \"[[Instant Crush]]\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2013/04/daft-punk-tease-new-music-at-coachella-featuring-julian-casablancas-and-panda-bear/ |title=Daft Punk tease new music at Coachella, collaborations with Julian Casablancas and Panda Bear |last=Young |first=Alex |date=April 13, 2013 |website=Consequence of Sound |access-date=September 27, 2014}}</ref><ref>Album booklet included with release of ''Random Access Memories'' credits him with words and the guitar solo</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/julian-casablancas-reveals-second-daft-punk-collab-20140331|title=Casablancas Reveals Second Daft Punk Collab|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=October 25, 2017}}</ref> The album won the 2013 [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year]], with Casablancas as one of the co-recipients of the award.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=Julian+Casablancas&field_nominee_work_value=Random+Access+Memories&year=All&genre=All |title=Past Winners Search |date=January 26, 2014 |publisher=grammy.com |access-date=January 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, it was revealed that Casablancas had worked on a song with [[Savages (band)|Savages]]' [[Camille Berthomier|Jehnny Beth]]. The collaboration was later announced to be a cover of \"[[Dagger & Guitar#Track listing|Boy/Girl]]\", a 1983 duet by Danish punk band [[Sort Sol]] and [[Lydia Lunch]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/1845956/julian-casablancas-jehnny-beth-collaboration-is-a-dutch-punk-cover-out-next-month/news/|title=Julian Casablancas & Jehnny Beth Collaboration Is A Danish Punk Cover Out Next Month|last1=DeVille|first1=Chris|website=Stereogum|accessdate=December 10, 2015}}</ref> The music video, directed by [[Warren Fu]], was released on December 4, 2015. The 7\" was released through both Cult Records and Pop Noire Records on December 18, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/59377-julian-casablancas-and-savages-jehnny-beth-cover-sort-sol-and-lydia-lunchs-boygirl/|title=Julian Casablancas and Savages' Jehnny Beth Cover Sort Sol and Lydia Lunch's \"Boy/Girl\"|last1=Beauchemin|first1=Molly|last2=Monroe|first2=Jazz|website=Pitchfork|accessdate=December 10, 2015}}</ref> Casablancas also wrote the song \"Youth Without Love\" for Har Mar Superstar's 2016 album ''Best Summer Ever'',<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bennett|first1=Kim Taylor|title=Har Mar Superstar: \"It Amazes Me How Much People Expect Musicians to be Waifs\"|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/65zanz/har-mar-superstar-best-summer-ever-body-shaming|publisher=Noisey|accessdate=November 1, 2017}}</ref> and is featured on \"No One There\", a song by Indian-born musician, Hammarsing Kharhmar (Exhibition).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/premieres/hear-strokes-julian-casablancas-sing-on-new-exhibition-song-w474907|title=Hear Julian Casablancas Lend Vocals to One of His Favorite New Acts|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=October 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Cult Records ===\nIn 2009, Casablancas founded [[Cult Records]], the creative imprint for his solo album ''[[Phrazes for the Young]]''. The label subsequently signed a partnership agreement with [[Kobalt Label Services]] in 2014, which includes representation and product management, physical distribution across multiple territories, digital distribution through [[AWAL]], marketing and sync licensing services.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stassen|first1=Murray|title=Kobalt Label Services partners with Cult Records|url=http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/kobalt-label-services-partners-with-cult-records/058825|accessdate=November 1, 2017|publisher=Music Week|date=June 25, 2014}}</ref> Cult currently represents [[The Growlers]], [[Har Mar Superstar]], [[Songhoy Blues]], [[Rey Pila]], [[Karen O]], Promiseland, The Strokes, The Voidz, Exhibition and [[Cerebral Ballzy]]. The label has also released works of Albert Hammond Jr., [[The Virgins]], Reputante, INHEAVEN, Exclamation Pony and Nelson London (C O L O R).\n\nCasablancas served as a co-producer on Rey Pila's album released on Cult, ''[[The Future Sugar (Rey Pila album)|The Future Sugar]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lange|first1=Maggie|title=Let Julian Casablancas' New Favorite Band Rey Pila Electrify Your Evening|url=https://www.gq.com/story/rey-pila-julian-casablancas-future-sugar|accessdate=November 1, 2017|publisher=GQ|date=September 24, 2015}}</ref> In August 2016, Cult Records announced a new album with [[The Growlers]], a Southern California-based band. It was also announced that Casablancas himself was producing the album, later known as ''[[City Club (album)|City Club]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2016/07/cult-records-announces-new-growlers-album-fall-tou.html|title=Cult Records Announces New Growlers Album, Fall Tour|access-date=August 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Musical influences ==\n[[File:Lou Reed (5900407225).jpg|thumb|200px|right|Casablancas recognized [[Lou Reed]] as a key influence on his musical style]]\nCasablancas claims that one of his earliest musical influences was [[The Doors]]- musically and instrumentally, in particular, rather than through the identity of [[Jim Morrison]] as a frontman.<ref name=\":4\" /> He has also cited [[Lou Reed]] of [[The Velvet Underground]] as a major influence on his lyrics and singing style. \"The way Lou Reed wrote and sang about drugs and sex, about the people around him \u2014 it was so matter-of-fact,\" Casablancas stated in a ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' interview. \"Reed could be romantic in the way he portrayed these crazy situations, but he was also intensely real. It was poetry and journalism.\"\n\nAdditionally, he has stated that [[Bob Marley]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americansongwriter.com/2010/08/drinks-with-julian-casablancas/|title=Drinks With: Julian Casablancas|last=Matheny|first=Skip|date=August 2, 2010|website=American Songwriter|publisher=AmericanSongwriter.com|accessdate=September 18, 2011}}</ref> [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] and [[Pearl Jam]] are major influences on his work, the latter being the reason he started making music, upon hearing the song \"[[Yellow Ledbetter]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/the-strokes-elegantly-wasted-20031113|title=The Strokes: Elegantly Wasted|last=Strauss|first=Neil|date=November 13, 2003|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=September 27, 2014}}</ref> Julian, in agreement with several members of The Voidz, has named [[Stevie Wonder]] as being a composer with a \u201cnext level mind\".<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Personal life ==\nJulian Casablancas has several half-siblings, including an elder sister from his father's first marriage,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://people.com/archive/someone-old-someone-new-vol-39-no-10/|title=Someone Old, Someone New \u2013 Vol. 39 No. 10|date=March 15, 1999|work=PEOPLE|language=en-US}}</ref> and three other siblings from the third marriage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/21/nyregion/john-casablancas-modeling-visionary-dies-at-70.html|title=John Casablancas, Modeling Visionary, Dies at 70|last=Wilson|first=Eric|date=July 20, 2013|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, he married Juliet Joslin, who was the assistant manager of The Strokes at the time.<ref name=\"save you\" /> Their son, Cal, was born in January 2010.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cleveland.com/popmusic/index.ssf/2010/04/for_julian_casablancas_life_go.html|title=For Julian Casablancas, life goes on without the Strokes|last=Soeder|first=John|date=April 1, 2010|work=The Plain Dealer|access-date=November 1, 2017|language=en-US|quote=Casablancas said of his son, Cal, born in January}}</ref> Their second son, Zephyr, was born March 27, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chatting with Julian Casablancas|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pUmuytn_Wao|website=YouTube|accessdate=28 March 2018}}</ref> They divorced in 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-strokes-brooklyn-bridge-to-chorus-978812/|title=The Strokes Go New Wave on Latest Single \u2018Brooklyn Bridge to Chorus|last=Shaffer|first=Claire|date=April 6, 2020|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=April 6, 2020|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nHe has maintained a sober lifestyle since 2009.<ref>{{cite web|author=David Renshaw Oct 18, 2014 12:40 pm BST |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/julian-casablancas-21-1237616 |title=Julian Casablancas: 'I was hungover for five years' |publisher=NME |date=2014-10-18 |accessdate=2019-06-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Patrick Doyle |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/22-things-you-learn-hanging-out-with-julian-casablancas-190764/ |title=22 Things You Learn Hanging Out With Julian Casablancas |work=Rolling Stone |date=2014-10-28 |accessdate=2019-06-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Power |first=Ed |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/the-growing-pains-of-julian-casablancas-1813477.html |title=The growing pains of Julian Casablancas |publisher=The Independent |date=2009-11-02 |accessdate=2019-06-20}}</ref>\n\n=== Politics ===\nIn recent years, Julian has become increasingly more vocal about his political interests, and has concluded that there is a direct parallel between politics and music.<ref name=\":2\" /> Though he claims the reelection of [[George W. Bush]] was the catalyst for his political intrigue, this link between political thought and music became much more evident upon the 2018 release of The Voidz\u2019 album, ''Virtue,'' through which he more explicitly expresses politically-charged ideas.<ref name=\":3\" /> Doing so, Casablancas explains, is using his music as a \u201cmeans to an end to make the world a better place.\u201d<ref name=\":3\" /> The music industry, according to Casablancas, operates quite similarly to the political world, where \u201cwhoever\u2019s propaganda\u2019s the loudest\u201d is what is popular, regardless of its quality.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 2016 Casablancas interviewed [[Henry Giroux]], during which they discuss the idea of whether or not the average American identifies that there are still existing struggles and conflicts that need to be addressed within the country.<ref>{{Citation|last=Rolling Stone|title=Julian Casablancas Interviews Henry Giroux|date=2016-09-13|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hLRWPsIzSOo&list=RD94hM2wkA1mw&index=3|access-date=2018-11-15}}</ref> Amongst various other issues impending on society today, Casablancas is most concerned with the idea that institutions have become more powerful than democratic government.<ref name=\":3\" /> He proposes that there is a perpetual conflict between those who understand that the democratic nature of the U.S. is lost and those who seek to keep it that way.<ref name=\":3\" /> It is in this way that the music industry reflects the nature of politics- quality and integrity is compromised under the control of capitalist greed.\n\nCasablancas cites some of his most politically influential figures as [[Oliver Stone]], [[Chris Hedges]], [[Jesse Ventura]], and [[Howard Zinn]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> He notes [[Martin Luther King Jr.]] as his favorite philosopher, whose work, Casablancas claims, held truth as an important standard value.<ref name=\":3\" /> He recognizes [[Paul Robeson]] as someone who used his musical platform to help further his serious political intrigue and as someone who, therefore, serves as a role model for politically engaged musicians.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nCasablancas has been a guest on ''[[Redacted Tonight]]'', as well as included its host, Lee Camp, as an opener for a Voidz show in Houston, Texas in October 2018.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nCasablancas endorsed Senator [[Bernie Sanders]] for the [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries]], and performed with his band at a rally in the [[University of New Hampshire]] the night before the New Hampshire primary.<ref> {{url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/01/the-strokes-bernie-sanders-rally-in-new-hampshire/}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy and influence ==\n[[Courtney Love]]'s song \"But Julian, I'm a Little Bit Older Than You\", from her debut solo album ''[[America's Sweetheart (album)|America's Sweetheart]]'' (2004), was written about Julian Casablancas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/courtney-love/5806|title=Courtney Love : California Ventura Theatre on|date=November 6, 2001|publisher=Nme.com|accessdate=March 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe has also served as inspiration for several other musicians including [[Alex Turner]] of the [[Arctic Monkeys]] and the painter [[Elizabeth Peyton]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.artnet.fr/artistes/elizabeth-peyton/julian-a-ewh86UBWVWlrs8DPiRN0rw2 |title=Elizabeth Peyton \u2013 Julian |publisher=Artnet.fr |access-date=March 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n'''Solo'''\n{{Main|Julian Casablancas discography}}\n* ''[[Phrazes for the Young]]'' (2009)\n\n\n'''The Strokes'''\n{{main|The Strokes discography}}\n* ''[[Is This It]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Room on Fire]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[First Impressions of Earth]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Angles (The Strokes album)|Angles]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Comedown Machine]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[The New Abnormal]]'' (2020)\n\n\n'''The Voidz'''\n{{main|The Voidz discography}}\n* ''[[Tyranny (The Voidz album)|Tyranny]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Virtue (The Voidz album)|Virtue]]'' (2018)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Julian Casablancas}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Julian Casablancas}}\n* {{Official website|http://juliancasablancas.com/main/}}\n\n{{Julian Casablancas}}\n{{The Strokes}}\n{{The Voidz}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Casablancas, Julian}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Institut Le Rosey]]\n[[Category:American baritones]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American rock singers]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American rock songwriters]]\n[[Category:American male songwriters]]\n[[Category:American people of Catalan descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Danish descent]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Singers from New York City]]\n[[Category:The Strokes members]]\n[[Category:Lyc\u00e9e Fran\u00e7ais de New York alumni]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n", "name_user": "Ajev8561", "label": "safe", "comment": "I added in the name of his sister: Cecile Casablancas", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Julian_Casablancas"}
