e news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/29/china-coronavirus-anti-foreigner-feeling-imported-cases |title='They see my blue eyes then jump back'\u2014China sees a new wave of xenophobia |first1=Lily |last1=Kuo |first2=Helen |last2=Davidson| name-list-format = vanc |date=29 March 2020 |work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"diario6April\">{{cite web |title=Espa\u00f1a registra un aumento del 47% en la mortalidad pero los expertos piden tiempo para relacionarlo con el coronavirus |url=https://www.eldiario.es/sociedad/Espana-registra-mortalidad-relacionarlo-coronavirus_0_1013849053.html |access-date=7 April 2020 |language=es |date=6 April 2020 |first=Oriol Sol\u00e9 |last=Altimira |first2=Ra\u00fal |last2=S\u00e1nchez| name-list-format = vanc}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"AFPhigh\">{{cite news |title=WHO says global risk of China virus is 'high' |url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/world/2020/01/27/who-says-global-risk-of-china-virus-is-039high039 |accessdate=18 April 2020 |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |date=27 January 2020}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"KesslerApril17\">{{cite news |last1=Kessler |first1=Glenn |title=Trump's false claim that the WHO said the coronavirus was 'not communicable' |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/04/17/trumps-false-claim-that-who-said-coronavirus-was-not-communicable/ |accessdate=18 April 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=17 April 2020 |archiveurl=http://archive.is/7Pgq4 |archivedate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"KennedyJanuary30\">{{cite news |last1=Kennedy |first1=Merrit |title=WHO Declares Coronavirus Outbreak A Global Health Emergency |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/01/30/798894428/who-declares-coronavirus-outbreak-a-global-health-emergency |accessdate=18 April 2020 |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"KuoJanuary21\">{{cite news |last1=Kuo |first1=Lily |title=China confirms human-to-human transmission of coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/20/coronavirus-spreads-to-beijing-as-china-confirms-new-cases |accessdate=18 April 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=21 January 2020}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"RobertsonApril7\">{{cite web |last1=Robertson |first1=Lori |title=The HHS Inspector General Report |url=https://www.factcheck.org/2020/04/the-hhs-inspector-general-report/ |publisher=[[Factcheck.org]] |accessdate=21 April 2020 |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Horton 18 March\">{{cite web |last=Horton |first=Richard |authorlink=Richard Horton (editor) |title=Scientists have been sounding the alarm on coronavirus for months. Why did Britain fail to act? |website=the Guardian |date=18 March 2020 |url=http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/mar/18/coronavirus-uk-expert-advice-wrong | access-date=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"dashboard Covid19 France\">{{cite web|url=https://dashboard.covid19.data.gouv.fr/|title=COVID-19 en France|publisher=Sant\u00e9 Publique France|language=fr|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"lepoint2369173\">{{cite web|url=https://www.lepoint.fr/sante/coronavirus-la-bombe-atomique-du-rassemblement-evangelique-de-mulhouse-28-03-2020-2369173_40.php|title=Coronavirus : la \" bombe atomique \" du rassemblement \u00e9vang\u00e9lique de Mulhouse|date=28 March 2020|website=Le Point}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"francetvinfo3889133\">{{cite web|url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/sante/maladie/coronavirus/video-coronavirus-le-nombre-de-contaminations-lors-du-rassemblement-evangelique-de-mulhouse-a-ete-largement-sous-evalue_3889133.html|title=ENQUETE FRANCEINFO. \"La majorit\u00e9 des personnes \u00e9taient contamin\u00e9es\" : de la Corse \u00e0 l'outre-mer, comment le rassemblement \u00e9vang\u00e9lique de Mulhouse a diffus\u00e9 le coronavirus dans toute la France|date=28 March 2020|website=Franceinfo}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"bbc51892477\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-51892477|title=Coronavirus: Spain and France announce sweeping restrictions|work=BBC News|date=15 March 2020|accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"independent9405136\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/coronavirus-france-lockdown-cases-update-covid-19-macron-a9405136.html|title=France imposes 15-day lockdown as part of emergency coronavirus response|date=16 March 2020|website=The Independent}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"macron13april\">{{cite news|url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/sante/maladie/coronavirus/direct-coronavirus-prolongation-du-confinement-reouverture-des-ecoles-et-des-commerces-regardez-l-allocution-televisee-d-emmanuel-macron_3913673.html|title=Coronavirus : prolongation du confinement jusqu'au 11 mai|date=13 April 2020|publisher=[[France Info (TV channel)|France Info]]|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=ft529354>[https://www.ft.com/video/96240572-7e35-4fcd-aecb-8f503d529354 Macron: coronavirus is Europe's 'moment of truth'] 16 April 2020, ''www.ft.com'', accessed 18 April 2020</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"AutoQ7-3\">[https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/world/coronavirus-maps.html Coronavirus Map: Tracking the Global Outbreak] ''The New York Times''. Retrieved 4{{nbsp}}April 2020.</ref>\n</references></div>\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Sister project links|voy=2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic|c=category:COVID-19 pandemic|d=Q81068910|q=2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|b=no|v=no|s=Category:COVID-19|m=no|mw=no|wikt=COVID-19|species=Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|n=Category:COVID-19}}\n{{Scholia}}\n\n===Health agencies===\n\n* [https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019 COVID-19] ([http://www.who.int/news-room/q-a-detail/q-a-coronaviruses Questions & Answers], [https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLbpi6ZahtOH5PLTT1yfXxcxDsNM40N1uG instructional videos]) by the [[World Health Organization]]\n* [https://www.ecdc.europa.eu/en/novel-coronavirus-china COVID-19] ([http://www.ecdc.europa.eu/en/novel-coronavirus-china/questions-answers Q&A]) by the [[European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control]]\n* [http://en.nhc.gov.cn/antivirusfight.html COVID-19] by the [[China National Health Commission]]\n* [https://www.moh.gov.sg/covid-19 COVID-19] ([http://www.moh.gov.sg/covid-19/faqs Q&A]) by the [[Singapore Ministry of Health]]\n* [https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/index.html COVID-19] ([https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/about/index.html Q&A]) by the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|U.S. Centers for Disease Control]]\n* [https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/emres/2019_ncov.html Coronavirus Disease 2019] ([https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/docs/2018-130/pdfs/2018-130.pdf?id=10.26616/NIOSHPUB2018130 Q&A]) by the [[National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health]]\n* [https://www.hpsc.ie/a-z/respiratory/coronavirus/novelcoronavirus/ COVID-19] by the [[Health Protection Surveillance Centre]], Ireland\n\n===Directories===\n\n* [https://curlie.org/Health/Conditions_and_Diseases/Respiratory_Disorders/COVID-19/ COVID-19 Directory on Curlie]\n* [https://openmd.com/directory/covid-19 COVID-19 Resource Directory on OpenMD]\n\n===Data and graphs===\n\n* [https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/situation-reports/ Coronavirus disease (COVID-2019) situation reports] and [https://who.sprinklr.com/ map] by the World Health Organization\n* [https://www.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6 Coronavirus COVID-19 Global Cases] and [https://github.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19 historical data] created by [[Lauren Gardner (scientist)|Lauren Gardner]] at [[Johns Hopkins University]]\n* [https://www.ecdc.europa.eu/en/publications-data/download-todays-data-geographic-distribution-covid-19-cases-worldwide Historical data about COVID-19 cases] published by the [[European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control]] (ECDC)\n* [http://unwfp.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/42b8837bb25049b9b1f69a9555d55808 World Travel Restrictions] based on [[World Food Programme|WFP]] data\n* [https://covid.observer Coronavirus Observer] based on [[Johns Hopkins University]] data\n* [https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/ Covid-19 coronavirus pandemic] published by [[worldometers.info|Worldometer]]\n* [https://ourworldindata.org/coronavirus Coronavirus Disease (COVID-19) Statistics and Research] published by ''[[Our World in Data]]''\n* [https://covid19.healthdata.org/united-states-of-america COVID-19 Projections] for many countries published by [[Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation]]\n* [https://sites.google.com/site/pandemicdata/ Historical data with additional computations and graphs in user-friendly spreadsheet format] created by [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/User:Dianelos Dianelos Georgoudis]\n* [https://gabgoh.github.io/COVID/index.html Epidemic Calculator]\n\n===Medical journals===\n\n* [https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/pages/coronavirus-alert Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19)] by ''[[JAMA (journal)|JAMA]]''\n* [https://www.bmj.com/coronavirus Coronavirus: News and Resources] by [[BMJ (company)|BMJ Publishing Group]]\n* [https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center Novel Coronavirus Information Center] by [[Elsevier]]\n* [https://www.thelancet.com/coronavirus COVID-19 Resource Centre] by ''[[The Lancet]]''\n* [https://www.springernature.com/gp/researchers/campaigns/coronavirus SARS\u2011CoV\u20112 and COVID-19] by ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]''\n* [https://www.nejm.org/coronavirus Coronavirus (Covid-19)] by ''[[The New England Journal of Medicine]]''\n* [https://novel-coronavirus.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/ Covid-19: Novel Coronavirus] by [[Wiley (publisher)|Wiley Publishing]]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|short=yes}}<!--Do not remove \"short=yes\" without previewing the page to make sure there is no \"Warning: Template include size is too large\" error displayed. It will not render correctly and will place this article in an error category.-->\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2019-20 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic| ]]\n[[Category:2010s disease outbreaks]]\n[[Category:2019 disasters in Asia]]\n[[Category:2019 disasters in China]]\n[[Category:2019 health disasters]]\n[[Category:2019 in international relations]]\n[[Category:2020 disasters in Asia]]\n[[Category:2020 health disasters]]\n[[Category:2020 in international relations]]\n[[Category:2020s disease outbreaks]]\n[[Category:21st-century epidemics]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Atypical pneumonias]]\n[[Category:Current events]]\n[[Category:December 2019 events in China]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in China]]\n[[Category:Health disasters in China]]\n[[Category:History of Wuhan]]\n[[Category:January 2020 events in China]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in China]]\n[[Category:Occupational safety and health]]\n[[Category:Pandemics]]\n[[Category:Public Health Emergency of International Concern]]\n", "name_user": "Ixfd64", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEpidemiology:c/e", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic"}
{"title_page": "Bomberman Legends", "text_new": "{{Infobox video game\n|title      = Bomberman Legends\n|image      = JaguarBomberman cover.jpg\n|caption    = Mockup cover art\n|developer  = Genetic Fantasia\n|publisher  = [[Atari Corporation]]\n|programmer = Jeremy Mika<br />Mike Mika<br />Robert Baffy\n|artist     = Jeff Burke <!-- One of the original developers of the unreleased game mentioned his name in a now-deleted tweet -->\n|series     = ''[[Bomberman]]''\n|platforms  = [[Atari Jaguar]]\n|released   = Unreleased\n|genre      = [[Action game|Action]], [[List of maze video games|maze]]\n|modes      = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''Bomberman Legends''''', also known as '''''Jaguar Bomberman''''', is an unreleased [[Action game|action]]-[[List of maze video games|maze]] [[video game]] that was in development by Genetic Fantasia and planned to be published by [[Atari Corporation]] for the [[Atari Jaguar]].<ref name=\"JBa\">{{cite web|last=Reutter|first=Hans|url=http://www.cyberroach.com/jaguarcd/html/jagbombr.htm|title=Unreleased Or Unfinished Jaguar Games - Jaguar Bomberman|website=cyberroach.com|accessdate=2018-10-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171001053208/http://www.cyberroach.com/jaguarcd/html/jagbombr.htm|archive-date=2017-10-01|url-status=live}}</ref> It was going to be a unique entry in the ''[[Bomberman]]'' [[List of video game franchises|franchise]], featuring its own dedicated [[Single-player video game|single-player]] and [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]] modes, with the latter having support for up to eight players by using two [[Atari Jaguar#Peripherals|Team Tap adapters]].<ref name=\"JBb\">{{cite web|last=Larrabee|first=Kevin|url=http://backinmyplay.com/episode-30-mike-mikas-time-machine-part-i/|title=Episode 30: Mike Mika\u2019s Time Machine (Part I)|website=backinmyplay.com|date=July 5, 2014|accessdate=2018-10-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825114730/http://backinmyplay.com/episode-30-mike-mikas-time-machine-part-i/|archive-date=2018-08-25|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe idea of creating a ''Bomberman'' title for the Jaguar was primarily hatched by Genetic Fantasia, which was a development company that was formed by Mike Mika,<ref name=\"JBc\">{{cite web|url=https://gamehistory.org/who-we-are/|title=Who We Are|publisher=[[Video Game History Foundation]]|accessdate=2018-10-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613204104/https://gamehistory.org/who-we-are/|archive-date=2018-06-13|url-status=live}}</ref> along with his colleagues to Atari Corp. during a behind-the-scenes meeting at Las Vegas in 1994, with the team looking at ''[[Super Bomberman 2]]'' in order to replicate its gameplay mechanics on the system.<ref name=\"JBb\"/><ref name=\"JBd\">{{cite web|last=Wallett|first=Adrian|url=https://www.arcadeattack.co.uk/mike-mika/|title=Mike Mika (Atari) \u2013 Interview|publisher=arcadeattack.co.uk|date=January 27, 2017|accessdate=2018-10-28|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923014523/https://www.arcadeattack.co.uk/mike-mika/|archivedate=23 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"JBz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.atarihq.com/jeo/jeo_0302.htm#TOP4|title=Jaguar Explorer Online - Volume 3, Issue 2|website=atarihq.com|date=November 19, 1999|accessdate=2018-11-22|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004102452/http://www.atarihq.com/jeo/jeo_0302.htm|archivedate=4 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThough Atari acquired the license of ''Bomberman'' from [[Hudson Soft]] between 1994 and 1995, the project would be discontinued by the former sometime in 1996 along with other upcoming projects for the platform such as ''[[Black ICE\\White Noise]]''  and ''[[Thea Realm Fighters]]'',<ref name=\"JBb\"/><ref name=\"JBe\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/stream/GamePro_Issue_079_February_1996#page/n18/mode/1up|title=ProNews: Atari Axes New Games|magazine=[[GamePro]]|issue=79|publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]]|date=February 1996|page=17}}</ref> due to Atari preparing to drop support for the Jaguar before merging with [[JT Storage]] in a [[reverse takeover]] on April of the same year.<ref name=\"JBa\"/><ref name=\"JBf\">{{cite web|url=http://contracts.onecle.com/atari/jt.mer.1996.04.08.shtml|title=Atari and JT Storage Reorganisation Plan|website= onecle.com|accessdate=2018-10-28|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061209123854/http://contracts.onecle.com/atari/jt.mer.1996.04.08.shtml|archivedate=December 9, 2006|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"JBg\">{{Cite web |url=http://google.brand.edgar-online.com/displayfilinginfo.aspx?FilingID=261582-33477-51099&type=sect |title=ATARI CORP Annual Report (Regulation S-K, item 405) (10-K405) ITEM 7. MANAGEMENT'S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS OF FINANCIAL CONDITION AND RESULTS OF OPERATIONS |access-date=2018-09-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612143052/http://google.brand.edgar-online.com/displayfilinginfo.aspx?FilingID=261582-33477-51099&type=sect |archive-date=2018-06-12 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Bomberman Legends'' was never previewed or mentioned in magazines and other publications at the time when the title was still being developed, until its existence was revealed during an online Q&A session hosted by ''Next Generation'' on April 1998.<ref name=\"JBh\">{{cite web|url=http://www.atarihq.com/jeo/jeo_0202.htm#CYBERCHATTER|title=Jaguar Explorer Online - Volume 2, Issue 2|website=atarihq.com|date=July 20, 1998|accessdate=2018-10-28|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004101628/http://www.atarihq.com/jeo/jeo_0202.htm|archivedate=4 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"JBi\">{{cite web|author=fsporsche|url=http://www.atarihq.com/cgi-bin/ji2_showmsg.pl?58316|title=Jag Bomberman completed...|website=atarihq.com|date=June 16, 2008|accessdate=2018-10-28|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101020220304/http://www.atarihq.com/cgi-bin/ji2_showmsg.pl?58316|archivedate=20 October 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> The game was also thought to be lost, before its [[source code]] was eventually recovered in recent years by two of the original programmers of the title.<ref name=\"JBj\">{{cite web|last=Mika|first=Mike|url=https://twitter.com/MikeJMika/status/470702580318756864|title=We may have just found the long lost Jaguar Bomberman|publisher=[[Twitter]]|date=May 25, 2014|accessdate=2018-10-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180925111517/https://twitter.com/MikeJMika/status/470702580318756864|archive-date=2018-09-25|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Gameplay ==\n[[File:JAG Bomberman Legends.jpg|thumb|left|Gameplay screenshot from one of the recently revealed beta builds.]]\n''Bomberman Legends'' is an action-maze game that plays very similarly like other games in the ''Bomberman'' franchise. There were going to be two gameplay modes: a single-player story mode,<ref name=\"JBz\"/> which took elements from titles of the series that were released at the time such as ''[[Super Bomberman]]'' and ''[[Bomberman '93]]'', with plans to feature an extensive storyline and cutscenes, and a multiplayer mode which supports up to eight players by plugging two Team Tap [[Multitap#Fifth generation|multitap]]s into the console.<ref name=\"JBb\"/>\n\n== Development ==\nAccording to Mike Mika, one of the original programmers for the project, him and his colleagues were still in college with their studies but they had aspirations of entering into the [[video game industry]].<ref name=\"JBb\"/> In 1994, the group travelled to Las Vegas and formed a game development company to discuss with multiple console manufacturers at [[Consumer Electronics Show|SCES '94]] and obtain a development kit in order to begin working on titles for systems that were still active on the market, such as the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]].<ref name=\"JBb\"/><ref name=\"JBd\"/> The team approached to Atari Corporation and began discussing with [[Jeff Minter]], known for his work in ''[[Tempest 2000]]'' on the Jaguar, who recommended them to speak with Atari Corp. representative Normen Kowalewski, which in turn he told them to meet him behind the scenes at a hotel. When the group arrived to the location, Atari had a Jaguar development setup along with a prototype of the [[Atari Jaguar CD]] add-on for demonstration purposes to [[third-party developer]]s.<ref name=\"JBb\"/> Interested in acquiring a development kit for the system, the team spoke with company representatives in regards to the subject and reached an agreement, purchasing and receiving various hardware kits to program games for the system.<ref name=\"JBb\"/>\n\nDuring a brainstorming session, the team originally had plans to create an project that was a spoof of the [[damsel in distress]] plot found in various titles at the time, but the idea was later discarded after publishers showed little interest in it, however, they later settled down in creating a Bomberman title as their \"dream game\", with Mike himself contacting Hudson Soft via online in regards to develop a title of the series for the Jaguar.<ref name=\"JBb\"/> He discussed with an employee of the company named Bill Rich and told that Atari was interested in acquiring the rights of the series, with the latter agreeing to do so after speaking with Hudson, and the team started development of ''Bomberman Legends'' between late 1994 and early 1995.<ref name=\"JBb\"/> The development team took care in making the title as faithful to the series, by looking at ''Super Bomberman 2'' on the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System]] as the standard, while they sent notes to Hudson in regards as to how they approached its development.<ref name=\"JBb\"/>\n\nSometime during development, Mike and his team received a telephone call from then-Atari Corporation vice-president in third-party development Bill Rehbock, who told to them if they could remove any reference to Bomberman due to monetary issues that Atari was having during this period and make it an original property instead.<ref name=\"JBb\"/> A few days later, the team received another call from Bill, who told them that Atari was preparing to stop support for the Jaguar and cancelled upcoming projects for the system,<ref name=\"JBe\"/> including ''Bomberman Legends'' and Atari merged with [[JT Storage]] in a [[reverse takeover]] on April 1996.<ref name=\"JBb\"/><ref name=\"JBd\"/><ref name=\"JBf\"/><ref name=\"JBg\"/><ref name=\"JBh\"/> Prior to its discontinuation, the team managed to get the multiplayer mode working, while the single-player mode had just begun development.<ref name=\"JBb\"/> It was never advertised or mentioned in any publication during its development.\n\n=== Reveal ===\nThe existence of ''Bomberman Legends'' was first hinted by ''[[Ultra Game Players]]'' magazine via their website, until it was officially confirmed to the public at an online Q&A session hosted by ''Next Generation'' magazine on April 2, 1998, revealing that one of their then-current staff members (Mike Mika, who began writing for the magazine as early as March 1998<ref name=\"JBk\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/details/NextGeneration39Mar1998/page/n3|title=Introducing - Editorial|magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|issue=39|publisher=[[Future US|Imagine Media]]|date=March 1998|page=2}}</ref>) previously worked on the unreleased game and one of the reasons as to why the project was ceased by Atari.<ref name=\"JBa\"/><ref name=\"JBh\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Glenn|url=http://www.atarihq.com/cgi-bin/ji2_showmsg.pl?58318|title=Re:Jag Bomberman completed...|website=atarihq.com|date=June 18, 2008|accessdate=2018-10-28|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101020220302/http://www.atarihq.com/cgi-bin/ji2_showmsg.pl?58318|archivedate=20 October 2010|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Jeff|url=http://www.atarihq.com/cgi-bin/ji2_showmsg.pl?58319|title=Re:Re:Jag Bomberman completed...|website=atarihq.com|date=June 18, 2008|accessdate=2018-10-28|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101020220302/http://www.atarihq.com/cgi-bin/ji2_showmsg.pl?58319|archivedate=20 October 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> During another online Q&A session hosted by ''Next Generation'' on July 24 of the same year, the name of the developer who worked on the project was revealed to be Genetic Fantasia, and that the company was based on Michigan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atarihq.com/jeo/jeo_0203.htm#CYBERCHATTER|title=Jaguar Explorer Online - Volume 2, Issue 3|website=atarihq.com|date=October 18, 1998|accessdate=2018-10-28|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004102128/http://www.atarihq.com/jeo/jeo_0203.htm|archivedate=4 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The game was briefly mentioned in an October 2000 issue of ''[[GameFan]]'' magazine during an article written by Eric C. Mylonas on \"The Graveyard\" section, with Eric suggesting Songbird Productions to publish the title.<ref name=\"JBl\">{{cite magazine|last=C. Mylonas|first=Eric|url=https://archive.org/stream/Gamefan_Vol_8_Issue_10#page/n108/mode/1up|title=The Graveyard - 2 Bona Fide NEW Jaguar Games!?! - Hyper Force|magazine=[[GameFan]]|volume=8|issue=10|date=October 2000|page=105|access-date=2018-09-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190105033351/https://archive.org/stream/Gamefan_Vol_8_Issue_10#page/n108/mode/1up#page/n108/mode/1up|archive-date=2019-01-05|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Rediscovery ===\nOn May 25, 2014, the source code of ''Bomberman Legends'' that was originally thought to be lost was found on a CD-ROM and eventually preserved by Mike and his brother Jeremy Mike, who was one of the lead programmers of the title, along with a member of the Jaguar community.<ref name=\"JBb\"/><ref name=\"JBd\"/><ref name=\"JBj\"/> More information about the project were revealed on [[Twitter]] posts written by Mike,<ref>{{cite web|last=Mika|first=Mike|url=https://twitter.com/MikeJMika/status/740236065068351488|title=Another #WhatIfGame that almost happened w/@jeremymika & @BobBaffy - Bomberman for Atari Jaguar. Cancelled Mid-Dev|publisher=[[Twitter]]|date=June 7, 2016|accessdate=2018-10-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180925111624/https://twitter.com/MikeJMika/status/740236065068351488|archive-date=2018-09-25|url-status=live}}</ref> including a never-before-seen production artwork of the game that was showcased to the public on June 26, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mika|first=Mike|url=https://twitter.com/MikeJMika/status/747183860144824320|title=More production artwork from Atari Jaguar Bomberman. These were scanned & cleaned digitally for the in-game intro|publisher=[[Twitter]]|date=June 26, 2016|accessdate=2018-10-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180925111728/https://twitter.com/MikeJMika/status/747183860144824320|archive-date=2018-09-25|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Bomberman series}}\n{{Portal bar|1990s|United States|Video games}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bomberman Legends}}\n[[Category:Atari games]]\n[[Category:Bomberman]]\n[[Category:Cancelled Atari Jaguar games]]\n[[Category:Hudson Soft games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox video game\n|title      = Bomberman Legends\n|image      = JaguarBomberman cover.jpg\n|caption    = Mockup cover art\n|developer  = Genetic Fantasia\n|publisher  = [[Atari Corporation]]\n|programmer = Jeremy Mika<br />Mike Mika<br />Robert Baffy\n|artist     = Jeff Burke <!-- One of the original developers of the unreleased game mentioned his name in a now-deleted tweet -->\n|series     = ''[[Bomberman]]''\n|platforms  = [[Atari Jaguar]]\n|released   = Unreleased\n|genre      = [[Action game|Action]], [[List of maze video games|maze]]\n|modes      = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''Bomberman Legends''''', also known as '''''Jaguar Bomberman''''', is an unreleased [[Action game|action]]-[[List of maze video games|maze]] [[video game]] that was in development by Genetic Fantasia and planned to be published by [[Atari Corporation]] for the [[Atari Jaguar]].<ref name=\"JBa\">{{cite web|last=Reutter|first=Hans|url=http://www.cyberroach.com/jaguarcd/html/jagbombr.htm|title=Unreleased Or Unfinished Jaguar Games - Jaguar Bomberman|website=cyberroach.com|accessdate=2018-10-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171001053208/http://www.cyberroach.com/jaguarcd/html/jagbombr.htm|archive-date=2017-10-01|url-status=live}}</ref> It was going to be a unique entry in the ''[[Bomberman]]'' [[List of video game franchises|franchise]], featuring its own dedicated [[Single-player video game|single-player]] and [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]] modes, with the latter having support for up to eight players by using two [[Atari Jaguar#Peripherals|Team Tap adapters]].<ref name=\"JBb\">{{cite web|last=Larrabee|first=Kevin|url=http://backinmyplay.com/episode-30-mike-mikas-time-machine-part-i/|title=Episode 30: Mike Mika\u2019s Time Machine (Part I)|website=backinmyplay.com|date=July 5, 2014|accessdate=2018-10-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825114730/http://backinmyplay.com/episode-30-mike-mikas-time-machine-part-i/|archive-date=2018-08-25|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe idea of creating a ''Bomberman'' title for the Jaguar was primarily hatched by Genetic Fantasia, which was a development company that was formed by Mike Mika,<ref name=\"JBc\">{{cite web|url=https://gamehistory.org/who-we-are/|title=Who We Are|publisher=[[Video Game History Foundation]]|accessdate=2018-10-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613204104/https://gamehistory.org/who-we-are/|archive-date=2018-06-13|url-status=live}}</ref> along with his colleagues to Atari Corp. during a behind-the-scenes meeting at Las Vegas in 1994, with the team looking at ''[[Super Bomberman 2]]'' in order to replicate its gameplay mechanics on the system.<ref name=\"JBb\"/><ref name=\"JBd\">{{cite web|last=Wallett|first=Adrian|url=https://www.arcadeattack.co.uk/mike-mika/|title=Mike Mika (Atari) \u2013 Interview|publisher=arcadeattack.co.uk|date=January 27, 2017|accessdate=2018-10-28|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923014523/https://www.arcadeattack.co.uk/mike-mika/|archivedate=23 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"JBz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.atarihq.com/jeo/jeo_0302.htm#TOP4|title=Jaguar Explorer Online - Volume 3, Issue 2|website=atarihq.com|date=November 19, 1999|accessdate=2018-11-22|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004102452/http://www.atarihq.com/jeo/jeo_0302.htm|archivedate=4 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThough Atari acquired the license of ''Bomberman'' from [[Hudson Soft]] between 1994 and 1995, the project would be discontinued by the former sometime in 1996 along with other upcoming projects for the platform such as ''[[Black ICE\\White Noise]]''  and ''[[Thea Realm Fighters]]'',<ref name=\"JBb\"/><ref name=\"JBe\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/stream/GamePro_Issue_079_February_1996#page/n18/mode/1up|title=ProNews: Atari Axes New Games|magazine=[[GamePro]]|issue=79|publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]]|date=February 1996|page=17}}</ref> due to Atari preparing to drop support for the Jaguar before merging with [[JT Storage]] in a [[reverse takeover]] on April of the same year.<ref name=\"JBa\"/><ref name=\"JBf\">{{cite web|url=http://contracts.onecle.com/atari/jt.mer.1996.04.08.shtml|title=Atari and JT Storage Reorganisation Plan|website= onecle.com|accessdate=2018-10-28|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061209123854/http://contracts.onecle.com/atari/jt.mer.1996.04.08.shtml|archivedate=December 9, 2006|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"JBg\">{{Cite web |url=http://google.brand.edgar-online.com/displayfilinginfo.aspx?FilingID=261582-33477-51099&type=sect |title=ATARI CORP Annual Report (Regulation S-K, item 405) (10-K405) ITEM 7. MANAGEMENT'S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS OF FINANCIAL CONDITION AND RESULTS OF OPERATIONS |access-date=2018-09-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612143052/http://google.brand.edgar-online.com/displayfilinginfo.aspx?FilingID=261582-33477-51099&type=sect |archive-date=2018-06-12 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Bomberman Legends'' was never previewed or mentioned in magazines and other publications at the time when the title was still being developed, until its existence was revealed during an online Q&A session hosted by ''Next Generation'' on April 1998.<ref name=\"JBh\">{{cite web|url=http://www.atarihq.com/jeo/jeo_0202.htm#CYBERCHATTER|title=Jaguar Explorer Online - Volume 2, Issue 2|website=atarihq.com|date=July 20, 1998|accessdate=2018-10-28|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004101628/http://www.atarihq.com/jeo/jeo_0202.htm|archivedate=4 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"JBi\">{{cite web|author=fsporsche|url=http://www.atarihq.com/cgi-bin/ji2_showmsg.pl?58316|title=Jag Bomberman completed...|website=atarihq.com|date=June 16, 2008|accessdate=2018-10-28|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101020220304/http://www.atarihq.com/cgi-bin/ji2_showmsg.pl?58316|archivedate=20 October 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> The game was also thought to be lost, before its [[source code]] was eventually recovered in recent years by two of the original programmers of the title.<ref name=\"JBj\">{{cite web|last=Mika|first=Mike|url=https://twitter.com/MikeJMika/status/470702580318756864|title=We may have just found the long lost Jaguar Bomberman|publisher=[[Twitter]]|date=May 25, 2014|accessdate=2018-10-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180925111517/https://twitter.com/MikeJMika/status/470702580318756864|archive-date=2018-09-25|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Gameplay ==\n[[File:JAG Bomberman Legends.jpg|thumb|left|Gameplay screenshot from one of the recently revealed beta builds.]]\n''Bomberman Legends'' is an action-maze game that plays very similarly like other games in the ''Bomberman'' franchise. There were going to be two gameplay modes: a single-player story mode,<ref name=\"JBz\"/> which took elements from titles of the series that were released at the time such as ''[[Super Bomberman]]'' and ''[[Bomberman '93]]'', with plans to feature an extensive storyline and cutscenes, and a multiplayer mode which supports up to eight players by plugging two Team Tap [[Multitap#Fifth generation|multitap]]s into the console.<ref name=\"JBb\"/>\n\n== Development ==\nAccording to Mike Mika, one of the original programmers for the project, him and his colleagues were still in college with their studies but they had aspirations of entering into the [[video game industry]].<ref name=\"JBb\"/> In 1994, the group travelled to Las Vegas and formed a game development company to discuss with multiple console manufacturers at [[Consumer Electronics Show|SCES '94]] and obtain a development kit in order to begin working on titles for systems that were still active on the market, such as the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]].<ref name=\"JBb\"/><ref name=\"JBd\"/> The team approached to Atari Corporation and began discussing with [[Jeff Minter]], known for his work in ''[[Tempest 2000]]'' on the Jaguar, who recommended them to speak with Atari Corp. representative Normen Kowalewski, which in turn he told them to meet him behind the scenes at a hotel. When the group arrived to the location, Atari had a Jaguar development setup along with a prototype of the [[Atari Jaguar CD]] add-on for demonstration purposes to [[third-party developer]]s.<ref name=\"JBb\"/> Interested in acquiring a development kit for the system, the team spoke with company representatives in regards to the subject and reached an agreement, purchasing and receiving various hardware kits to program games for the system.<ref name=\"JBb\"/>\n\nDuring a brainstorming session, the team originally had plans to create an project that was a spoof of the [[damsel in distress]] plot found in various titles at the time, but the idea was later discarded after publishers showed little interest in it, however, they later settled down in creating a Bomberman title as their \"dream game\", with Mike himself contacting Hudson Soft via online in regards to develop a title of the series for the Jaguar.<ref name=\"JBb\"/> He discussed with an employee of the company named Bill Rich and told that Atari was interested in acquiring the rights of the series, with the latter agreeing to do so after speaking with Hudson, and the team started development of ''Bomberman Legends'' between late 1994 and early 1995.<ref name=\"JBb\"/> The development team took care in making the title as faithful to the series, by looking at ''Super Bomberman 2'' on the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System]] as the standard, while they sent notes to Hudson in regards as to how they approached its development.<ref name=\"JBb\"/>\n\nSometime during development, Mike and his team received a telephone call from then-Atari Corporation vice-president in third-party development Bill Rehbock, who told to them if they could remove any reference to Bomberman due to monetary issues that Atari was having during this period and make it an original property instead.<ref name=\"JBb\"/> A few days later, the team received another call from Bill, who told them that Atari was preparing to stop support for the Jaguar and cancelled upcoming projects for the system,<ref name=\"JBe\"/> including ''Bomberman Legends'' and Atari merged with [[JT Storage]] in a [[reverse takeover]] on April 1996.<ref name=\"JBb\"/><ref name=\"JBd\"/><ref name=\"JBf\"/><ref name=\"JBg\"/><ref name=\"JBh\"/> Prior to its discontinuation, the team managed to get the multiplayer mode working, while the single-player mode had just begun development.<ref name=\"JBb\"/> It was never advertised or mentioned in any publication during its development.\n\n=== Reveal ===\nThe existence of ''Bomberman Legends'' was first hinted by ''[[Ultra Game Players]]'' magazine via their website, until it was officially confirmed to the public at an online Q&A session hosted by ''Next Generation'' magazine on April 2, 1998, revealing that one of their then-current staff members (Mike Mika, who began writing for the magazine as early as March 1998<ref name=\"JBk\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/details/NextGeneration39Mar1998/page/n3|title=Introducing - Editorial|magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|issue=39|publisher=[[Future US|Imagine Media]]|date=March 1998|page=2}}</ref>) previously worked on the unreleased game and one of the reasons as to why the project was ceased by Atari.<ref name=\"JBa\"/><ref name=\"JBh\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Glenn|url=http://www.atarihq.com/cgi-bin/ji2_showmsg.pl?58318|title=Re:Jag Bomberman completed...|website=atarihq.com|date=June 18, 2008|accessdate=2018-10-28|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101020220302/http://www.atarihq.com/cgi-bin/ji2_showmsg.pl?58318|archivedate=20 October 2010|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Jeff|url=http://www.atarihq.com/cgi-bin/ji2_showmsg.pl?58319|title=Re:Re:Jag Bomberman completed...|website=atarihq.com|date=June 18, 2008|accessdate=2018-10-28|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101020220302/http://www.atarihq.com/cgi-bin/ji2_showmsg.pl?58319|archivedate=20 October 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> During another online Q&A session hosted by ''Next Generation'' on July 24 of the same year, the name of the developer who worked on the project was revealed to be Genetic Fantasia, and that the company was based on Michigan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atarihq.com/jeo/jeo_0203.htm#CYBERCHATTER|title=Jaguar Explorer Online - Volume 2, Issue 3|website=atarihq.com|date=October 18, 1998|accessdate=2018-10-28|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004102128/http://www.atarihq.com/jeo/jeo_0203.htm|archivedate=4 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The game was briefly mentioned in an October 2000 issue of ''[[GameFan]]'' magazine during an article written by Eric C. Mylonas on \"The Graveyard\" section, with Eric suggesting Songbird Productions to publish the title.<ref name=\"JBl\">{{cite magazine|last=C. Mylonas|first=Eric|url=https://archive.org/stream/Gamefan_Vol_8_Issue_10#page/n108/mode/1up|title=The Graveyard - 2 Bona Fide NEW Jaguar Games!?! - Hyper Force|magazine=[[GameFan]]|volume=8|issue=10|date=October 2000|page=105|access-date=2018-09-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190105033351/https://archive.org/stream/Gamefan_Vol_8_Issue_10#page/n108/mode/1up#page/n108/mode/1up|archive-date=2019-01-05|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Rediscovery ===\nOn May 25, 2014, the source code of ''Bomberman Legends'' that was originally thought to be lost was found on a CD-ROM and eventually preserved by Mike and his brother Jeremy Mike, who was one of the lead programmers of the title, along with a member of the Jaguar community.<ref name=\"JBb\"/><ref name=\"JBd\"/><ref name=\"JBj\"/> More information about the project were revealed on [[Twitter]] posts written by Mike,<ref>{{cite web|last=Mika|first=Mike|url=https://twitter.com/MikeJMika/status/740236065068351488|title=Another #WhatIfGame that almost happened w/@jeremymika & @BobBaffy - Bomberman for Atari Jaguar. Cancelled Mid-Dev|publisher=[[Twitter]]|date=June 7, 2016|accessdate=2018-10-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180925111624/https://twitter.com/MikeJMika/status/740236065068351488|archive-date=2018-09-25|url-status=live}}</ref> including a never-before-seen production artwork of the game that was showcased to the public on June 26, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mika|first=Mike|url=https://twitter.com/MikeJMika/status/747183860144824320|title=More production artwork from Atari Jaguar Bomberman. These were scanned & cleaned digitally for the in-game intro|publisher=[[Twitter]]|date=June 26, 2016|accessdate=2018-10-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180925111728/https://twitter.com/MikeJMika/status/747183860144824320|archive-date=2018-09-25|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Bomberman series}}\n{{Portal bar|1990s|United States|Video games}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bomberman Legends}}\n[[Category:Atari games]]\n[[Category:Bomberman]]\n[[Category:Cancelled Atari Jaguar games]]\n[[Category:Hudson Soft games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "KGRAMR", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bomberman_Legends"}
